<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lobbying for China Trade Steps Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- When lawmakers opened their hometown  
newspapers recently, they found full-page ads from the Business 
Roundtable declaring that China's growing economy meant an 
increased appetite for U.S. food, cars and semiconductors. 
</P>
<P>
	When their aides brought in the mail, they found letters from  
the U.S. Chamber of Commerce with exact figures on how much in 
products and services their home states exported to China last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	And when they returned home for the Fourth of July recess, they  
found local members of the National Association of Manufacturers on 
their schedules for meetings to discuss China trade. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've just been making a point (that) at every one of those  
meetings ... somebody stands up and says, `I want to explain the 
importance of the China issue to the American manufacturing 
community,''' said Howard Lewis, the NAM's vice president for 
economic policy. 
</P>
<P>
	After a bumpy year in U.S.-Chinese relations, the U.S. business  
community is taking nothing for granted in its annual battle to 
renew China's normal trade relations with the United States. U.S. 
businesses exported $18 billion in goods and services to China last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton announced on June 3 he was renewing the  
status, but Congress has 90 days to overturn it if it chooses. 
Lawmakers are set to vote as early as this week. 
</P>
<P>
	The business lobby particularly is concerned that a bipartisan  
congressional investigation that recently concluded Beijing stole 
U.S. nuclear secrets might jeopardize the decision to allow free 
trade between China and the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is harder,'' acknowledged Rep. Amo Houghton, R-N.Y., former  
chief executive officer of Corning Inc., known for its 
glass-science breakthroughs, and a strong supporter of normal trade 
relations with China. 
</P>
<P>
	The stepped-up lobbying effort is visible everywhere. For  
instance, the Business Roundtable targeted just a dozen lawmakers 
last year during its China trade lobbying efforts. This year, its 
sights are set on 100. 
</P>
<P>
	``There has not been an issue more heavily lobbied,'' Rep.  
Sherrod Brown, D-Ohio, acknowledged. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Chamber of Commerce officials argue that normal trade  
relations and problems outlined in the espionage report by the 
committee led by Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., are separate 
issues. 
</P>
<P>
	``Espionage is a way of life. We have to protect against it.  
That has nothing to do with trade,'' chamber lobbyist William 
Morley said. He is telling lawmakers that their vote will be 
counted when the organization compiles its annual vote ratings. 
</P>
<P>
	The chamber's president, Tom Donohue, delivered a similar  
message to Cox, who agrees that the two issues should not be 
linked. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is possible to have any China policy one wishes while  
attending to the counterintelligence and security problems in our 
report,'' Cox said in an interview. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents cite both the Cox report and the 1996 campaign finance  
scandal as reasons for rejecting normal trade relations. Rep. Frank 
Wolf, R-Va., brings it up during his discussions with GOP freshmen, 
urging them to vote no. 
</P>
<P>
	Likewise, Republican presidential candidate Gary Bauer has made  
his opposition to China trade well-known. ``I'm a janitor's son, 
and I believe in free enterprise, but I don't believe in putting 
your country second and putting your profits first,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters are hoping for an overwhelming vote of support to  
give impetus to efforts to bring China into the World Trade 
Organization. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to sending heavyweight corporate executives to talk  
to lawmakers on Capitol Hill, they also have asked lower-level 
employees in congressional districts to call the district offices 
of their local representatives to deliver the same message: Free 
trade means jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Each lawmaker has gotten a letter from the Chamber of Commerce  
with state-by-state statistics showing the value of trade with 
China. For example, New York exported $679 million worth of goods 
in 1998, California $2.4 billion. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
