<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Arraignment Expected in Yosemite Murder  
</P>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- A hotel maintenance man who was  
arrested in the beheading of a naturalist at Yosemite National Park 
is expected to be arraigned tomorrow, the FBI said today. Cary 
Stayner was accused of killing Joie Ruth Armstrong, 26, whose 
decapitated body was found near her Yosemite housing on Thursday. 
Stayner is also a suspect in the killings of three park sightseers 
earlier this year. The 38-year-old man was arrested yesterday. 

</P>
<P>
	Shuttle May Have Leaked Fuel  
</P>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Space shuttle Columbia may have been  
leaking hydrogen fuel all the way to orbit last week from one of 
its main engines, NASA said today. If it proves to be a leak as 
photographs suggest, the engine could have shut down abruptly if 
more fuel had seeped out, resulting in a never-before-attempted 
emergency landing within minutes of launch. As it turned out, 
Columbia made it safely to orbit Friday under the control of Air 
Force Col. Eileen Collins, the first woman to command a U.S. 
spaceship. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Urges Calm in China, Taiwan  
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Washington's top liaison with Taiwan today  
urged Beijing and Taipei to cool tensions and avoid war, but said 
the United States would not mediate between them. Richard Bush said 
Washington wanted the two sides to engage in more dialogue and 
avoid provocations, an apparent criticism of a recent statement by 
Taiwan President Lee Teng-hui that demanded Taiwan and China be 
recognized as equally legitimate states. 

</P>
<P>
	World Leaders Attend Hassan Funeral  
</P>
<P>
	RABAT, Morocco (AP) -- World leaders walked solemnly through  
screaming crowds in this ancient North African capital today to 
honor Hassan II, for 38 years king of a poor, placid nation 
committed to peace in a tumultuous region. Hundreds of thousands of 
Moroccans, wailing and chanting in the July sun, watched the royal 
cortege and its escort of Western, European, Middle Eastern, 
African and Asian heads of state, including President Clinton. 
Hassan died Friday at age 70. 

</P>
<P>
	Test-Tube Babies Can Trace Parents  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- As the world's first test-tube baby celebrated her  
21st birthday today, the government announced plans to give 
children born from donated sperm or eggs the right in adulthood to 
trace the donors. The announcement dismayed the country's largest 
donor organization, which said there would be a fall in donors, 
fearful of being traced decades later by offspring who are total 
strangers. The Department of Health said a consultation paper will 
be published in the next few months on ways of changing the law 
that guarantees anonymity to donors. 

</P>
<P>
	Pope Laments Treatment of Elderly  
</P>
<P>
	CASTEL GANDOLFO, Italy (AP) -- Himself slowed down by old age,  
Pope John Paul II today lamented that the elderly are increasingly 
shunted to the sidelines of advanced societies. ``In societies with 
advanced industrial and technological development, the condition of 
the elderly is ambivalent,'' the pope said during his vacation in 
Castel Gandolfo. ``On one hand, they are ever less integrated into 
the family and social fabric. On the other hand, instead, their 
role becomes ever more important, above all for the care and 
education of grandchildren,'' John Paul continued, speaking from 
his balcony. 

</P>
<P>
	Internet Security Fights Back  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Internet security researchers at Georgia Tech  
believe the neural networks they are working on may be the key to 
stopping hackers. Even though Georgia Tech's The Sentinel Project 
doesn't ``think,'' the group of programs is set up in different 
``nodes'' much like a human brain. The network is designed to 
recognize abnormal data, which could signal that someone has broken 
into the system. 

</P>
<P>
	'Haunting' No. 1 at Box Office  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- ``The Haunting'' premiered at No. 1 at the  
box office with $33 million, according to industry estimates today. 
Another effects-laden movie, ``Inspector Gadget,'' debuted in 
second place with $22 million. The ``Star Wars'' prequel, 
meanwhile, crossed the $400 million mark to become the 
third-highest grossing movie of all time. 

</P>
<P>
	Orioles Defeat Angels 8-7  
</P>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Albert Belle hit three homers and had six RBIs,  
and Cal Ripken hit his 399th career homer and singled in the 
winning run in the 11th inning today as the Baltimore Orioles beat 
Anaheim 8-7, extending the Angels' losing streak to 10 games. 

</P>
<P>
	Armstrong Triumphs at Tour de France  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Lance Armstrong rode to victory in the Tour de  
France today, capping an amazing comeback from cancer and becoming 
just the second American to win cycling's showcase race. Near death 
two years ago, Armstrong sprinted to the finish line on the 
Champs-Elysees to claim the inspirational victory that had seemed 
certain for days. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ELIZABETH A. KENNEDY  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
