<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Schroeder Pushes Welfare State Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- Undaunted by attacks from leftist allies,  
Germany's chancellor on Sunday defended his ambitious plans to trim 
the country's welfare state and spur private enterprise in a bid to 
revive a sluggish economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Gerhard Schroeder, who has sought to emulate Britain's Tony  
Blair and President Clinton by pushing his Social Democrats party 
toward the political center, accused his left-wing critics of being 
out of touch with reality. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the overwhelming majority in my party and, by the way  
... the majority of voters, has understood the necessity of 
economizing,'' the chancellor said in an interview with German 
television ZDF. ``Whoever talks of anti-social imbalances simply 
has no idea.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Union leaders -- traditional allies of the Social Democrats -- and  
some in the party's own left-wing have attacked Shroeder's budget 
plans as heartless and socially irresponsible. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, the Cabinet approved an austerity budget for 2000  
that includes $16 billion in across-the-board cuts and $4.2 billion 
in corporate tax relief. Parliament is to vote on the package in 
the fall. 
</P>
<P>
	Finance Minister Hans Eichel, who wants to balance the budget in  
eight years, warned that more cuts were on the way. 
</P>
<P>
	``The efforts to save must become even greater,'' he was quoted  
as saying in Sunday's Bild am Sonntag newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	Schroeder was elected last fall primarily on a promise to put  
Germans back to work. But with unemployment still stuck above 10 
percent, his government's poll numbers have been in a steady 
decline. 
</P>
<P>
	His 9-month-old government has suffered from internal bickering  
between market-friendly forces led by the chancellor and old-style 
leftists. 
</P>
<P>
	Leftists, however, lost their most powerful advocate, Oskar  
Lafontaine, who left his post as finance minister in March, 
allowing Schroeder consolidate his grip. 
</P>
<P>
	In the television interview, Schroeder called the push for a  
balanced budget ``economically and politically correct,'' noting 
that the U.S. economy is booming in large part because it has 
already achieved it. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of Schroeder's critics were outraged at a report released  
last week by Economics Minister Werner Mueller, who called on 
Germans to show more personal initiative and reduce their 
dependence on state handouts. 
</P>
<P>
	Mueller, who has no party affiliation, suggested the government  
concentrate social programs on the ``really needy'' and called for 
a sharp cut in government spending relative to the private sector. 
</P>
<P>
	In a Sunday interview, Mueller denied he was trying to undo  
Germany's cherished welfare state built up in the postwar boom 
years, but only to ease the increasing demands on it. 
</P>
<P>
	``For decades, many believed that the state could solve every  
problem,'' he told Der Tagesspiegel newspaper. ``So it's difficult 
... to turn back this belief in a full-insurance state. But when 
the public treasury is empty, there's nothing else left.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
