<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Columbia, Mir Crews Chat in Orbit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) -- Space shuttle Columbia's astronauts  
took a break early Sunday to chat with the only other humans in 
orbit -- the three men aboard Russian space station Mir. 
</P>
<P>
	The radio chat was to be a conversation between Frenchmen Michel  
Tognini on Columbia and Jean-Pierre Haignere on Mir, but Mir's 
commander broke in to greet his counterpart on the shuttle, Eileen 
Collins. 
</P>
<P>
	Viktor Afanasyev congratulated Collins on becoming the first  
woman to command a U.S. space flight. After first trying to say it 
in English, Afanasyev settled for eloquence in his mother tongue. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to congratulate you from the bottom of my heart,''  
Afanasyev said in Russian. ``You are a courageous woman.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Spasibo,'' Collins replied, thanking him in Russian. She has  
visited Mir twice, in 1995 and 1997, when she served as a shuttle 
co-pilot. 
</P>
<P>
	The space travelers chatted in French, Russian and English  
across a ham radio link for about 10 minutes as Mir and Columbia 
soared some 7,700 miles apart. 
</P>
<P>
	It was something of a reunion for Tognini and Mir cosmonaut  
Sergei Avdeyev -- both spent two weeks aboard Mir in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	``Again we're flying together,'' Tognini said.  
</P>
<P>
	``We don't see each other but we can imagine each other,''  
Avdeyev responded. 
</P>
<P>
	Tognini congratulated Avdeyev, who holds the record for the most  
time in space -- 714 days over three flights. When Avdeyev returns 
to Earth at the end of August, he will have been on Mir for more 
than a year. 
</P>
<P>
	The conversation was a short break for the Columbia astronauts,  
who were spending their third day in space performing various 
scientific experiments. The experiments remain the focus for the 
crew members, who completed their main objective Friday by 
releasing the $1.5 billion Chandra X-ray Observatory into space. 
</P>
<P>
	Late Saturday, the first of five engine firings to boost  
Chandra's orbit was performed successfully. Another four rocket 
firings -- the next of which is scheduled for Sunday night -- will 
put the world's most powerful X-ray telescope in an orbit extending 
one-third of the way to the moon. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
