<DOCNO> APW19990725.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-25 14:50:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> UN-Iraq Deadlock Hurting Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) -- Consumer goods sales have come to a virtual  
standstill due to an all-time low demand, forced by Iraq's 
plummeting currency rate and growing uncertainty about the 
country's future, traders said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The situation is so grim that some of us are seriously  
thinking of shutting down,'' said Assaad Isameal, the owner of a 
clothing store in Arasat, Baghdad's most fashionable thoroughfare. 
</P>
<P>
	The downturn began after the December 1998 airstrikes on Iraq by  
the United States and Britain to punish it for forcing out U.N. 
weapons inspectors searching for Iraq's weapons of mass 
destruction. 
</P>
<P>
	Following the strikes, the Iraqi dinar nose-dived to 2,250 to a  
dollar after it had stayed firm around 1,500 during 1998. It is now 
hovering around 2,000. But consumer confidence remains weak amid 
dwindling hopes that the U.N. Security Council will act swiftly to 
lift U.N. sanctions imposed after Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait. 
</P>
<P>
	The sanctions cannot be removed until the council certifies that  
Iraq has gotten rid of all its illegal weapons. That objective 
remains unreachable while Iraq remains adamant about not allowing 
the resumption of weapons inspections. 
</P>
<P>
	The sanctions crippled Iraq's economy in the initial years, but  
many Iraqis, including commodities traders and transporters, began 
making money after the United Nations started the oil-for-food 
program in December 1996. The program allows Iraq to sell oil under 
U.N. supervision to buy food and other essential items for its 
people. 
</P>
<P>
	The free rations left many Iraqis with spare cash for the first  
time in years and Baghdad's shopping areas began to flourish last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	But traders say gloom has descended again as no one appears to  
know how the 7 1/2-month-old Iraq-U.N. crisis will unfold, especially 
since Security Council members themselves are divided over how to 
deal with Iraq. 
</P>
<P>
	Television shop owner Ahmed Mohammed cannot remember when he  
last sold a set. ``It was long time ago and I am afraid may not 
happen again,'' he said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Sinan Hussam, a tailor, said landlords are slashing rent to  
ensure tenants do not close businesses. But even his rent of around 
$5 dollars a day is hard to afford. ``To tell you the truth I am 
not earning (that) much,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
