<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Astronaut Tells of Bumpy Ride </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- As the first American woman in  
space, Sally Ride had to contend with reporters asking if she wept 
at work and with flight planners obsessing over whether she should 
take along makeup. 
</P>
<P>
	And after her space shuttle mission, she said, the attention was  
so intense she wished someone else had been first. 
</P>
<P>
	Sixteen years later, as commander of the orbiting Columbia,  
Eileen Collins has broken the shuttle program's last gender 
barrier. And while NASA no longer frets over makeup and 
menstruation aboard ship, the publicity factor hasn't changed. 
</P>
<P>
	``The hardest part of her flight is actually going to be the  
post-flight, all the attention that she gets, all the demands on 
her time,'' Ride said last week. ``She's going to be whisked from 
one public appearance to the next public appearance, and it's very 
trying, very stressful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Collins, a 42-year-old Air Force colonel, acknowledges she's not  
ready for the hoopla that awaits her following Tuesday night's 
scheduled landing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if you could ever be ready for it,'' she said  
from orbit over the weekend. But she promised to do her best ``to 
go out and spread the word.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ride, now 48, left NASA in 1987 after flying once more in space  
and is now a physics professor at the University of California at 
San Diego. She called Collins before the mission to wish her good 
luck, just as she did when Collins flew as the first female shuttle 
co-pilot in 1995. She was present for Collins' first launch attempt 
early Tuesday but had to leave before Columbia finally took off 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview following a women's aerospace panel discussion  
last Monday, Ride recalled how NASA shielded her from the press 
before her flight aboard Challenger in June 1983. She was too busy 
training as the crew's flight engineer and robot-arm operator to 
make speeches or do interviews, other than the traditional crew 
news conference a few weeks before launch. 
</P>
<P>
	A male reporter asked Ride if she wept when things go wrong; the  
question still annoys her. One journalist wanted to know if she 
planned to have children, and another wondered if she'd wear a bra 
in space. ``There is no sag in zero-g,'' she replied. 
</P>
<P>
	Although her shuttle crewmates and most everyone else at NASA  
were accustomed by then to working with female astronauts, at least 
on Earth, Ride said experimenters came up with all sorts of things 
to do ``to me or for me'' during the six-day flight. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was, `Oh my gosh, how do we handle a female who might  
have her period in orbit?' There was 'Hmmm, I wonder if we should 
be carrying makeup on space shuttle flights?''' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Makeup ended up on board, but Ride didn't use it. As for the  
``problem'' of menstruating astronauts, tampons simply were added 
to the shuttle toiletries kit. 
</P>
<P>
	Astronaut Steven Hawley, who was married to Ride during her  
space-flying days and happens to be aboard Columbia with Collins, 
remembers far more fuss made over his ex-wife than Collins. 
</P>
<P>
	``Part of that just could be that the shuttle program itself was  
much younger back then, and this was the first woman flying in any 
capacity,'' Hawley explained before the mission. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-seven American women have followed Ride into orbit, among  
them Mae Jemison, who became the first black woman in space in 
1992, and Shannon Lucid, who became the world's female space 
endurance champion with her six-month Mir mission in 1996. Teacher 
Christa McAuliffe never made it to space; she was killed in the 
1986 Challenger accident along with Judith Resnik, who two years 
earlier was the second American woman in space. 
</P>
<P>
	Ride said she never wanted or sought attention.  
</P>
<P>
	``My personality was the personality of a physicist who wanted  
to be an astronaut, not the personality of someone who wanted to be 
a public figure,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ride still guards her privacy. She recently made a cameo  
appearance on CBS-TV's ``Touched by an Angel'' and granted a few 
interviews during last week's countdown for Collins, but that's 
about it. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not so much that I don't like the attention. It's that I  
want to have a life. I want to be able to go to the supermarket. I 
want to be able to teach my classes. I want to be able to do 
research,'' she said. ``The nice thing about teaching at a 
university is that college students have to be cool, so they can't 
look like they're too excited.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
