<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Medical Journal Editor To Leave </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WALTHAM, Mass. (AP) -- The editor in chief of the New England  
Journal of Medicine will step down next year because of differences 
over administrative and publishing issues, the head of the group 
that publishes the journal said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Jerome P. Kassirer, 66, will begin a 7-month sabbatical on Sept.  
1, concluding his contract with the journal on March 31, 2000, said 
Dr. Jack T. Evjy, president of the Massachusetts Medical Society, 
which owns and publishes the journal. 
</P>
<P>
	``It became evident that, despite our mutual best efforts, Dr.  
Kassirer and the Medical Society were unable to find common ground 
on these matters,'' Evjy said. 
</P>
<P>
	An interim editor would likely be announced in the next two  
weeks, according to Frank Fortin, spokesman for the Massachusetts 
Medical Society. 
</P>
<P>
	Fortin refused to comment on what issues divided Kassirer and  
the society. 
</P>
<P>
	Envy said Kassirer achieved many accomplishments during his  
eight-year tenure at the journal. Some of those included shortening 
the turnaround time for manuscripts and bringing attention to 
critical medical developments. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am honored to have served as editor-in-chief of the New  
England Journal of Medicine and privileged to work with editors and 
staff who have never deviated from their singular focus on 
quality,'' Kassirer said in a statement. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
