<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Washington Bids Farewell to Kennedy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- An estimated 4,500 people gathered Sunday at a  
huge Catholic church in the nation's capital to pay respects to 
John F. Kennedy Jr., Carolyn Kennedy Bessette and Lauren Bessette. 
</P>
<P>
	The mass honoring the trio killed in an airplane crash July 16  
was held at the Basilica of the National Shrine of the Immaculate 
Conception, the largest Catholic church in the Western Hemisphere. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennedy ``was a symbol of a generation coming into its own,''  
said the Rev. William E. Lori, Auxiliary Bishop of Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	``He revered his famous father, shared the life of his famous  
family, yet carved out a path all his own,'' Lori said during the 
homily. ``Carolyn and Lauren, while not so completely in the 
spotlight, were women of accomplishment in their own right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eleanor Holmes Norton, District of Columbia's nonvoting delegate  
to the House of Representatives, said she came to the mass because 
Washington ``in many ways is Kennedy territory.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Not just John F. Kennedy, but this family changed this town,''  
Norton said. ``They came to a Southern town -- not terribly 
cosmopolitan. When they left, they left a world-class city.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also attending was the capital city's mayor, Anthony Williams.  
``Our city represents very much a national service, as well as on 
the local level,'' Williams said. ``John Kennedy contributed to 
that tradition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The mass drew Washingtonians as well as tourists from across the  
country. Some audience members were moved to tears. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been grieving all week. This will bring some closure,''  
said Trudy Gallager, 60, of Falls Church in suburban Virginia. 
``When you grew up in my day, you were told if you were a woman or 
Catholic, you couldn't be president. John Kennedy began to break 
through that.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
