<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Broncos Muse Chance of 'Three-Peat' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREELEY, Colo. (AP) -- Rod Smith has temporarily traded his  
traditional No. 80 practice jersey for No. 3 to remind his 
teammates of their potential place in NFL history. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Romanowski and Glenn Cadrez walked to lunch Sunday wearing  
T-shirts emblazoned with the words, ``Back to back to BACK.'' John 
Mobley arrived at training camp and promptly boasted ``Time for No. 
3.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Talk of winning an unprecedented third straight Super Bowl is  
hardly taboo among the Denver Broncos. In fact, it's motivation. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you come in and say, `We want to make the playoffs,' hell,  
you might as well not even play,'' Smith said. ``The thing is to 
win the Super Bowl. It just so happens that we're going for three 
in a row. It's something special, something that's never been done. 
Why wouldn't you want to address that? I'm not coming out here to 
go 7-9. I'm out here to win it all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The straightforward approach is a contrast to last year when  
Denver was pursuing a different piece of history. The Broncos won 
their first 13 games and tried to deflect all questions of joining 
the 1972 Miami Dolphins as the only team to finish the season 
undefeated. 
</P>
<P>
	The questions became moot when the New York Giants upset the  
Broncos in their bid for victory No. 14, but the prospect of being 
the first team to win three straight Super Bowls has led to a new 
buzz. 
</P>
<P>
	``Absolutely, it's in the back of your head,'' said defensive  
end Harald Hasselbach. ``You never like to talk about `three-peat,' 
but it's in your head.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Winning three straight titles would not be a first in the NFL.  
Green Bay captured the NFL championship in 1965 and then won the 
first two Super Bowls in 1966 and 1967. The Packers also finished 
as NFL champs from 1929-31. 
</P>
<P>
	Denver's quest is slightly more difficult considering there were  
24 teams in the NFL and AFL 33 years ago. The Broncos will have to 
emerge from a 31-team field this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every day people talk to us about the possibility to do  
something that no one else has ever done,'' head coach Mike 
Shanahan said. ``It's obviously there, but we understand that you 
don't win championships by talking about what's going to be done at 
the end of the season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aside from retired quarterback John Elway, the Broncos have a  
chance to win their third straight title with virtually the same 
lineup that pounded Atlanta in January and surprised Green Bay a 
year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Their personnel situation is similar to the Buffalo Bills, who  
made it to four straight Super Bowls in the '90s. Of course, the 
Bills made dubious history by losing all four games. 
</P>
<P>
	``I kind of look at their little run of four years straight,''  
running back Terrell Davis said. ``Had they won those four games 
... they would have been the only team to do it, so it's 
possible.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990725.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-25 18:20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rogers Introduced, Beltran Demoted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In his first attempt at pitching with a New York  
baseball team, Kenny Rogers had a mediocre record with the Yankees. 
He's confident things will change with the Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a little different because it's the National League  
and I've never been a National League pitcher before,'' Rogers said 
Sunday. ``But when I'm healthy I've proven that I'm a pretty good 
pitcher. ... one of the best in baseball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rogers, 34, who was 5-3 with a 4.30 ERA in 19 starts with  
Oakland this year, was traded to the Mets on Friday for minor 
leaguers Terrence Long and Leoner Vasquez. 
</P>
<P>
	In his two seasons with the Yankees in 1996 and 1997, Rogers was  
18-15 with a 5.16 ERA. 
</P>
<P>
	``My first year I thought I was pretty good,'' Rogers said,  
referring to the 1996 season when he was 12-8 with a 4.68 ERA in 30 
starts. ``But I look at it for myself because I want to do better 
here. The key is staying healthy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Opinions varied on Rogers' effort in New York two seasons ago.  
Some thought he was pitching with a bad shoulder, while others 
believed he felt too much pressure. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's a little too coincidental to say there was too  
much pressure,'' Rogers said. ``My second year, I was pretty much 
in limbo for most of the year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To make room for Rogers on their 25-man roster, the Mets  
optioned left-handed reliever Rigo Beltran to Triple-A Norfolk 
before the start of Sunday night's game with the Chicago Cubs. 
</P>
<P>
	Last season, Rogers was 16-8 with an 11-0 record at the Oakland  
Coliseum, becoming the first pitcher to go undefeated at home since 
Tommy Green was 10-0 at Philadelphia's Veterans Stadium in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	With his trade to the Mets, the left-hander rejoined manger  
Bobby Valentine, who managed Rogers during his first season in the 
majors with Texas in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	Valentine said he planned to give Rogers his first start  
Wednesday, when the Mets conclude a three-game series with the 
Pittsburgh Pirates. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you go out and do something like this, you want to make  
sure it fits,'' Valentine said. ``I think he'll fit. He's a good 
athlete and he knows how to pitch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets are looking for another pitcher to come out of the  
bullpen, but are satisfied with what Rogers might be able to give 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	``He (Rogers) is a quality left-handed pitcher,'' said Mets  
outfielder Brian McRae. ``There aren't a lot of lefties out there 
who are durable and can give you a lot of innings like he can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Beltran was 1-1 with a 3.48 ERA in 21 appearances with the Mets  
this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was happy when I heard (the Mets) got another starter,''  
said Beltran, who had been demoted to the minors three times before 
Sunday. ``But it's tough for me because I feel like I was doing the 
job here.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
