<DOCNO> APW19990725.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-25 12:01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Albright: US-China Tensions Easing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SINGAPORE (AP) -- The United States and China remained at odds on  
NATO's bombing of the Chinese embassy in Belgrade but showed signs 
Sunday that their tattered relations might be on the mend. 
</P>
<P>
	They also agreed the Taiwan crisis must be solved quickly.  
</P>
<P>
	After a lunch meeting with the Chinese foreign minister,  
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright cited an ``easing of 
tensions'' and ``the restoration of communication over a very 
friendly lunch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan announced that Chinese  
President Jiang Zemin has accepted President Clinton's offer to 
meet separately in New Zealand in September during an economic 
summit of Asian and Pacific nations. 
</P>
<P>
	Clearly, the Taiwan question remained touchy, although Albright  
said efforts by Taiwan's president to explain his provocative 
statements suggesting sovereignty ``thus far don't quite do it,'' 
and both she and Tang urged a peaceful resolution. 
</P>
<P>
	Tang refused to rule out force as an option, however, and  
cautioned the United States to avoid doing anything that would 
``fan the flames'' of Taiwanese independence. 
</P>
<P>
	The Albright-Tang meeting, held outside a conference of Asian  
leaders, was the highest-level contact between the two countries 
since the May 7 bombing in Yugoslavia that killed three Chinese 
citizens and injured more than 20 others. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Tang indicated China remains not persuaded the bombing  
was accidental despite repeated public and private assurances from 
American officials. 
</P>
<P>
	``They want additional reviews,'' said Albright. She said that  
even though the explanation would not change, more U.S. officials 
would go to Beijing to reiterate the U.S. position and to discuss 
compensation. 
</P>
<P>
	At his separate news conference, Tang said: ``The U.S.  
government should appropriately handle the Taiwan question and 
fully understand the damage the bombing incident has brought into 
this relationship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Albright-Tang session came at a conference of the  
Association of Southeast Asian Nations. On Monday, the 10 member 
nations will meet with a their more powerful partners, including 
the United States, Japan, Russia and Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright also met with India's foreign minister, Jaswant Singh.  
They talked about recent Indian clashes with Pakistan in disputed 
Kashmir and about India's imminent elections, U.S. officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The controversy over Taiwan, and the state of U.S.-Chinese  
relations, was a chief topic of conversation among leaders gathered 
for the conference, almost overshadowing talk about Asia's 
financial crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	China has expressed its indignation at comments earlier this  
month by Taiwan President Lee Teng-hui suggesting 
``state-to-state'' relations in the future. That appeared to 
undermine the so-called ``one-China'' policy under which the 
mainland and Taiwan have long coexisted. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright said Richard Bush, the U.S. envoy to Taiwan, made clear  
to Lee over the past few days ``that there needs to be ... a 
peaceful resolution to this and a dialogue. And I think that the 
explanations offered thus far don't quite do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Later, a senior administration official, speaking on the  
condition of anonymity, said Lee appeared to be looking for a way 
to put his earlier statements ``in context'' to not provoke a 
confrontation. ``This is still a work in progress,'' the official 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States has long been pledged to defend Taiwan in the  
event of an invasion from the mainland. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright said she brought up human rights issues with Tang,  
including China's recent crackdown on members of Falun Gong, an 
outlawed Buddhist-based spiritual movement. 
</P>
<P>
	``I did mention the fact that obviously there are sects in other  
countries that may create problems but that the right of assembly 
and the right for a peaceful expression of views is very 
important.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Albright said she and Tang also talked about the potential  
instability that could come to the region if North Korea goes ahead 
with a second multistage missile launch, like one it launched over 
Japan last August. Some experts suggest North Korea may test a 
missile in the next month capable of reaching Alaska or Hawaii. 
</P>
<P>
	Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer told reporters that  
any further missile testing by North Korea ``would be a very 
serious development in regional security.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yasuhisa Kawamura, a spokesman for Japan's Ministry of Foreign  
Affairs, said Tokyo may suspend a $1 billion contribution to a 
North Korean nuclear energy project if the North goes ahead with 
the missile test. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
