<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Clinton Attends Hassan Funeral  
</P>
<P>
	RABAT, Morocco (AP) -- Leaders from about 30 countries streamed  
into Morocco today for the funeral of King Hassan II, hailed as a 
peacemaker and anchor of the Arab world, while Moroccans arrived in 
droves to mourn their monarch and spiritual leader. President 
Clinton, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli President 
Ezer Weizman and Prime Minister Ehud Barak are among those 
attending this afternoon's funeral, expected to last six hours. The 
ceremony began with Koranic readings by the coffin in an ornate 
salon where Hassan II used to greet religious leaders during 
Ramadan. 

</P>
<P>
	West Bank Settlements Dismantled  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- In the first test of the new Israeli  
government's settlement policy, Prime Minister Ehud Barak ordered 
the dismantling of mobile homes set up illegally at a West Bank 
Jewish settlement, his office said today. Five mobile homes were 
dismantled by the army late last night and early this morning after 
they were set up yesterday about 20 miles north of Jerusalem. The 
future of the 144 Jewish settlements in the West Bank and Gaza 
Strip is to be discussed in talks on a permanent peace agreement. 
The Palestinians have said they expect Barak to freeze settlement 
building until the settlements' fate is determined. 

</P>
<P>
	Kosovo Govt. Meetings Postponed  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Kosovo's U.N. administrator today  
announced that Serb-Albanian provisional government meetings have 
been indefinitely postponed in the wake of the killings of 14 
Serbs. U.N. administrator Bernard Kouchner said tomorrow's meeting 
had been postponed, granting a Serb request. A Serb spokesman said 
the request was made to allow the Serbs to bury the victims. NATO 
troops today searched for the killers of the Serb farmers. 
Peacekeepers stepped up patrols in and around Gracko, the central 
Kosovo farming community where the men were killed by automatic 
weapons fire. 

</P>
<P>
	Report: China Plans Taiwan Exercises  
</P>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- In a sign that it has not forgiven Taiwan's  
assertion of statehood, China will conduct more naval exercises off 
the southeastern coast across the waters from Taiwan, a pro-Beijing 
newspaper reported today. Wen Wei Po and several independent Hong 
Kong newspapers also reported that the People's Liberation Army 
conducted joint sea and air exercises ahead of August 1, the 
anniversary of the army's founding. ``The People's Liberation Army 
has shown it is prepared to smash any separatist plans at any 
time,'' Wen Wei Po reported. 

</P>
<P>
	Tree Limb Snaps, Killing Three  
</P>
<P>
	BAY VILLAGE, Ohio (AP) -- A large tree limb fell about 35 feet  
onto a table and killed three people attending a backyard picnic 
last night, police said. It is unclear what caused the limb to 
snap. The National Weather Service said no strong winds were 
reported at the time of the accident in the suburb west of 
Cleveland. The tree limb, about 1 1/2 feet to 2 feet in diameter and 
35 feet long, was so large four men couldn't lift it. A 46-year-old 
woman died at the scene, a 30-year-old man died en route to St. 
John West Shore Hospital and a 32-year-old man died shortly after 
arriving at Lakewood hospital. 

</P>
<P>
	Man Questioned in Yosemite Death  
</P>
<P>
	YOSEMITE NATIONAL PARK, Calif. (AP) -- A motel maintenance man  
was detained for questioning yesterday in the decapitation of a 
naturalist in Yosemite National Park and the FBI has hinted at a 
possible link with the slaying of three park sightseers earlier 
this year. FBI agent James Maddock said no arrests had been made 
but he anticipated a ``significant announcement'' to be made today 
at Sacramento's FBI headquarters. Cary Stayner was found yesterday 
morning at a nudist colony near Sacramento, a Sacramento County 
source said. 

</P>
<P>
	Irvine Wins Austrian Grand Prix  
</P>
<P>
	SPIELBERG, Austria (AP) -- Eddie Irvine won the Austrian Grand  
Prix today, keeping alive Ferrari's hopes of its first Formula One 
championship in 20 years. Irvine held off David Coulthard to win 
his second race of the season. The victory moved him within two 
points of Mika Hakkinen, the defending champion who leads the 
drivers' standings. Ferrari is bidding for the title without 
Michael Schumacher, who broke his right leg at the British Grand 
Prix two weeks ago. 

</P>
<P>
	Ryan, Brett, Yount Head for Hall  
</P>
<P>
	COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. (AP) -- Nolan Ryan, who played longer than  
anyone in major league history, will take his place in the Hall of 
Fame today. Slugger Orlando Cepeda, George Brett and Robin Yount, 
part of the 3,000-hit club and the greatest players of their 
franchises, will join Ryan for the induction ceremonies. The 
largest Cooperstown class since 1972 also includes late umpire 
Nestor Chylak, Negro leagues ace Smokey Joe Williams and 
19th-century manager Frank Selee. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
  	   	
