<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	U.S., Vietnam Reach Trade Deal  
</P>
<P>
	HANOI, Vietnam (AP) -- The United States and Vietnam announced  
today they have reached a tentative trade agreement. The deal, 
which comes after three years of wrangling, still requires approval 
by the U.S. Congress and Vietnam's National Assembly. It's 
considered the last major step in normalizing relations following 
the Vietnam War that ended more than 24 years ago. The pact also 
could pave the way for Vietnam, one of the world's poorest nations, 
to join the World Trade Organization. 

</P>
<P>
	China Skeptical Over Bombing Explanation  
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE (AP) -- China also is not fully ready to accept U.S.  
assertions that the May 7 bombing of its embassy in Belgrade was an 
accident, China's foreign minister and Secretary of State Madeleine 
Albright suggested today. At separate news conferences after their 
luncheon meeting on the sidelines of a conference of Asian leaders 
Tang Jiaxuan said, ``This incident has seriously damaged the 
U.S.-China relationship and left a deep scar in the hearts of the 
Chinese people. We don't think we've reached the stage where we can 
say we are satisfied or not.'' 

</P>
