<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Daewoo Pledges To Restructure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- The head of ailing Daewoo group  
pledged to faithfully carry out a restructuring to regain trust 
from markets and investors in the conglomerate, which produces 
goods as diverse as ships, cars, electronics, clothes and 
pesticides. 
</P>
<P>
	``Daewoo will complete restructuring by the end of this year as  
promised, with cooperation from creditors, through objective and 
transparent procedure,'' chairman Kim Woo-choong said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The remarks were made at a press conference, which was hurriedly  
arranged one day after Economy and Finance Minister Kang Bong-kyun 
said Daewoo has to accelerate selling off assets to resolve its 
cash shortage or it could drag down the entire economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim said there have been unfounded rumors about the size of  
Daewoo's debts. He added that as of late June, Daewoo affiliates at 
home had a total of $40.8 billion in debts and its overseas units 
collectively had $6.84 billion in foreign-currency denominated 
loans. That compares to an estimated $65 billion in total assets. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the government said the central bank of Korea will  
supply up to $16.7 billion in emergency funds to investment trust 
companies in case they face problems because of a possible massive 
selloff of stock and bonds by small investors. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan aims to keep a key short-term interest rate from rising  
above the current 4.8 percent. Experts say higher interest rates 
could cause investors to pull money out of stock and other markets 
and hinder the ongoing restructuring at the nation's large 
conglomerates. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement was made after an emergency meeting among the  
government's top economic officials including the heads of the 
Ministry of Finance and Economy, the Financial Supervisory 
Commission and the Bank of Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	Daewoo narrowly escaped becoming South Korea's largest-ever  
bankruptcy when creditors agreed Monday to delay repayment of $8.3 
billion in short-term debt for six months and extend $3.3 billion 
in new loans. 
</P>
<P>
	In return, Daewoo put up $8.42 billion of stock and real estate  
as collateral. 
</P>
<P>
	But doubts persisted over Daewoo's commitment and its ability to  
carry out restructuring by selling off dozens of units within six 
months. The Korean Composite Stock Price Index plummeted 7.3 
percent on Friday, marking the third largest drop in the stock 
market's history. 
</P>
<P>
	Government officials said Daewoo will concentrate on its two  
main businesses -- the flagship trading arm Daewoo Corp. and Daewoo 
Motors, the nation's second largest carmaker -- and most of the 
other units will be sold off to raise funds. 
</P>
<P>
	They also said creditors will convert unpaid loans into equity  
to lower Daewoo's debt load from the fourth quarter of this year. 
Creditors began reviewing Daewoo's collateral Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The government of President Kim Dae-jung has been urging South  
Korea's bloated conglomerates to slim down to improve their 
financial condition. While other conglomerates were selling assets 
and focusing on profitability, Daewoo continued to expand. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
