<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Texas Hometown Cheers Armstrong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Karl Haussmann watched on the Internet as  
Lance Armstrong won the Tour de France, and was astounded. 
</P>
<P>
	``God, this is cool,'' said Haussmann, director of the Lance  
Armstrong Foundation for cancer research. ``This is amazing. It's 
Lance, it's the comeback, it's history.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Haussman was in his office by 8 a.m. Sunday. The European  
broadcast of a series of still photos from the race was sometimes 
fuzzy and digitally mangled. But it would take more than that to 
spoil Haussmann's day. 
</P>
<P>
	When the race started July 3, few thought Armstrong could win  
cycling's most prestigious and rugged race. After all, the 
27-year-old rider from Austin was recovering from testicular cancer 
that had spread to his lungs and brain. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, Armstrong has done it. He won in Paris by 7 minutes, 37  
seconds, and his adopted hometown was ready to celebrate. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sweet. It's a done deal,'' Haussmann said when images of  
Armstrong on the winner's podium appeared on his screen. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even though it was kind of anticlimactic because he had such a  
big lead, I still got an adrenaline rush -- my heart beating faster 
-- thinking about him leading the race and crossing the finish 
line,'' Haussmann said. 
</P>
<P>
	To many in Austin, Armstrong is a hero.  
</P>
<P>
	``Not only is he a hometown hero, he's a world hero,'' said John  
Crismond, who watched ABC's tape-delayed afternoon coverage with 
about 750 cycling enthusiasts during a party at the Copper Tank 
Brewing Co. The crowd was about 300 more than organizers expected. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously he didn't bring those problems upon himself, but  
he's chosen to carry the banner for people with cancer,'' said 
Crismond, who like many in the crowd wore yellow shirts 
representing the Tour leader. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong was diagnosed with cancer in 1996. He had surgery to  
remove lesions from his brain and one of his testicles. He 
underwent months of chemotherapy. His doctors say there is a tiny 
chance the cancer will return. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a guy who we saw with no hair, lying in bed barely  
able to move after brain surgery, and now he's won cycling's 
greatest race,'' Haussmann said. 
</P>
<P>
	The only other American to win the Tour de France was Greg  
LeMond, a three-time champion whose last victory came in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	By early Sunday, someone had left a basket of flowers on the  
doorstep of the Lance Armstrong Foundation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Keep rolling Lance,'' read one of several messages on the  
card. ``You are an inspiration.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some in Austin had thought Armstrong wouldn't live to see this  
year's race, let alone win it. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was so sick,'' said Sally Koch, a self-described ``terrible  
biker'' but a big Armstrong fan. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we read about his cancer that he had, it seemed like it  
was pretty much all over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jammed shoulder to shoulder in the restaurant, the crowd cheered  
every time Armstrong's face came on the television screens and 
quieted every time he spoke. 
</P>
<P>
	The fans also paused for the playing of ``The Star-Spangled  
Banner'' when Armstrong received the winner's trophy before letting 
out a final cheer. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was a phenomenal thing,'' said Renee Orr, who said she  
rode bicycles competitively until she had children. ``This really 
is a hometown boy done well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong lives part of the year in Austin and Nice, France. He  
will fly to New York this week for interviews before returning to 
France for several exhibition appearances, the Austin 
American-Statesman reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong will return to Austin on Aug. 10, his agent, Bill  
Stapleton, said. 
</P>
<P>
	The city is planning a parade and downtown festival upon  
Armstrong's return, said Mayor Kirk Watson, himself a testicular 
cancer survivor. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be emotional,'' Watson said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
