<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Latex Rats Used in Experiments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) -- Lab rats, take a load off.  
</P>
<P>
	A new high-tech, hand-crafted rubber rat eventually could save  
the lives of hundreds of thousands of rodents used in laboratory 
experiments each year, say animal rights activists and the Dutch 
pharmaceutical company that developed the lifelike latex 
substitute. 
</P>
<P>
	About 3,000 rats are killed annually for educational or research  
purposes in the Netherlands alone, where rats and mice are used in 
more than 500,000 tests a year, according to the Dutch anti-animal 
research group Animal Testing Free. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the Netherlands, the alternative will save a couple hundred  
rats per year, but it's about more than just the animals which will 
be saved. It is proof that there are realistic alternatives,'' said 
spokeswoman Marja Zuidgeest. 
</P>
<P>
	PVC-Rat, as the new product is called, made its debut in March  
after years of research and development. The rat is specifically 
designed for micro-surgical laboratory experiments in universities, 
hospitals and clinics. 
</P>
<P>
	Although one other company makes an artificial rat used for  
practicing intravenous and oral drug administration, the PVC-Rat is 
the first alternative upon which surgical operations can be 
conducted, said chairman Rene Remie of Microsurgical Developments, 
the creation's designer. 
</P>
<P>
	``It looks like a real rat, but it's lying on its back with its  
stomach open and you can see veins and the liver and other 
organs,'' said Puck Bossert of Belgium-based Solvay 
Pharmaceuticals, the product's manufacturer. 
</P>
<P>
	Live animals are needed to simulate life signs such as blood  
pressure, heart rate and breathing during surgery. But Bert 
Zutphen, a professor of laboratory animal science at the University 
of Utrecht, said artery stitching and nerve fusion can be practiced 
just as well on the fake rats, which can be used over and over by 
removing sutures after practice surgery, saving on laboratory 
costs. 
</P>
<P>
	``A dead rat is no good to anybody,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Medical experts believe the alternative rat -- which is made of  
recycled latex -- will replace some trials in the medical field, 
particularly those in which real rats are used in dissection to 
train university students. But they say real animals will always be 
needed for testing. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsurgical Developments was founded in the late 1980s with  
the goal of reducing the use of animals in laboratory experiments. 
The rat is the company's first breakthrough and international 
attention has spurred demand, Solvay says. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, which also makes simulation software for surgery,  
plans to refine the rat to enable the performance of more intricate 
``operations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Each life-sized animal costs about $150 to make, but with  
government subsidies they are sold for $125, including an extra set 
of synthetic organs. Although modest sales of 750 rats are 
projected for 1999, the two companies hope such rubbery rodents one 
day will replace half of the real thing in laboratories worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Zutphen began experimenting with about 150 of the fake rats last  
year. Though they'll never completely replace live rats, he said, 
they're sufficient for introductory surgical techniques. 
</P>
<P>
	``A large portion of surgery can be learned without the use of  
real animals,'' Zutphen said, ``but they will not replace live rats 
as an essential part of laboratory research.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990725.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-25 09:40:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coast Guard: JFK Search Not Unusual </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Ron Trenton took off in a Piper Cherokee from  
San Diego's Montgomery Field and headed toward the beach, waggling 
his wings at his fellow lifeguards below. 
</P>
<P>
	It was his routine goodbye before heading out over the Pacific  
Ocean on whale-watching expeditions. 
</P>
<P>
	But this was Trenton's last goodbye. Within hours he had become  
the object of one of the hundreds of searches the Coast Guard 
conducts every year for missing planes. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of these draw little notice from the general public. Not so  
the extensive search for John F. Kennedy Jr., his wife and 
sister-in-law, and many wonder whether the government would go to 
equal lengths for someone who wasn't the celebrity son of an 
assassinated president. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton assured the country that the initial efforts  
``were consistent with what would have been done in any other 
case.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But a review of rescue and recovery efforts in two single-engine  
airplane crashes off the California coast demonstrates the 
difficulty of setting a uniform standard for a search. Trenton's 
family has no complaints. But the sister of Robert Beach, who died 
with three friends in the other crash in question, sees a 
``difference between celebrity and civilian.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not so, says Larry Hall of the U.S. Coast Guard, who oversaw the  
search for Beach's plane. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't matter to us if you are John F. Kennedy Jr. or John  
Q. Citizen, we are in the business of saving lives,'' Hall said. 
``We will launch whatever resources it takes. Only when we have 
ruled out any chance of a survivor, and usually it's reluctantly, 
will we suspend the search.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the recovery efforts of bodies and wreckage vary, as does  
the number of people assigned to investigate the accidents, said 
Keith Holloway of the National Transportation Safety Board. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the NTSB investigated 1,907 private airplane  
accidents, including 361 fatal crashes. 
</P>
<P>
	Like Kennedy, both pilots in the California crashes were not  
trained on instruments and were flying in less-than-desirable 
conditions. Neither filed a flight plan, nor did they signal 
possible engine problems over the radio. 
</P>
<P>
	One important difference is water depth.  
</P>
<P>
	Kennedy crashed in about 180 feet of Atlantic Ocean off Martha's  
Vineyard. Beach is presumed to have gone down in 5,000 feet of 
water, and Trenton in a two-mile deep canyon on the ocean floor. 
</P>
<P>
	``We, of course, want to find out what caused the plane to  
crash,'' Holloway said. ``But it has to be within realistic limits 
of what can actually be accomplished.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trenton, 51, was an experienced pilot who had logged hundreds of  
hours when he took off Feb. 11, 1997 from San Diego to Santa 
Catalina Island, 35 miles away. 
</P>
<P>
	He ate lunch on the island, then headed home at about 3 p.m.,  
circling the island and climbing to 2,000 feet before heading east 
to San Diego, FAA radar records show. 
</P>
<P>
	At about 3:15 p.m., his plane began slowly descending. By 3:19  
p.m., he had disappeared from radar. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like he just coasted into the ocean,'' said his brother,  
Doug Trenton. 
</P>
<P>
	When the plane failed to arrive, a friend called authorities,  
kicking off what newspaper accounts would later call one of the 
most extensive searches in San Diego's history. 
</P>
<P>
	Using infrared radar, which detects temperature differences in  
the water, the first Coast Guard helicopter flew along Trenton's 
presumed route. Meanwhile, several boats also searched. 
</P>
<P>
	The initial search area was about 2,000 square miles, divided  
among rescuers, Lt. Drew Cromwell, a co-pilot on that first 
helicopter, recalled. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's a lot of ocean. You just keep going over the area, back  
and forth, back and forth,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	By the next morning, FAA records narrowed the area to 100 square  
miles. Four helicopters, six airplanes, five ships and two Navy 
vessels joined the search and Trenton's fellow lifeguards rented 
five more airplanes. (The first hours of the Kennedy search 
involved a Coast Guard jet, two helicopters, an Air Force C-130 as 
a command post and, later, 15 small planes and an array of boats.) 
</P>
<P>
	As in the Kennedy search, buoys with transmitters were used to  
help determine the ocean's drift. But by the end of the second day, 
hope was fading. At 56 degrees, the water temperature would be 
fatal. 
</P>
<P>
	``But there are just some people who refuse to die, even when  
science says they should,'' Cromwell said. ``We hold out hope for 
those people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the end of the third day, Coast Guard officials talked to the  
family about ending the search. The pilot was probably dead, they 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``But my parents asked them to keep searching and they did -- for  
two more days. They searched for my brother with the hope he might 
be alive for five days. That's longer than they did for Kennedy,'' 
Doug Trenton said. 
</P>
<P>
	No wreckage or debris was ever found. The cause of the accident  
is unknown. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ron was gone. We knew it. We grasped for five days for  
something, but rationally we knew he was gone,'' Trenton said. 
</P>
<P>
	But that's not the case for Kathy Lanni, sister of 37-year-old  
Robert Beach. 
</P>
<P>
	``The difference between celebrity and civilian,'' she told The  
Baltimore Sun in a recent interview. ``Of course, it's unfair. But 
it's the way it is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Beach took off from Half Moon Bay in Northern California on May  
22, 1998, in a rented Piper on a moonless night. 
</P>
<P>
	Within minutes, people reported seeing two white lights spinning  
into the ocean or hearing a splash in the water, said Paul Young, a 
member of the Auxiliary Coast Guard who interviewed the witnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	The Coast Guard issued an emergency broadcast -- a message that  
would play every 30 minutes for the next three days -- asking 
boaters and pilots in the area to keep an eye out for survivors and 
debris. 
</P>
<P>
	The Coast Guard then began its rescue attempt, said Sr. Petty  
Office Guy McNabb, who oversaw the effort. 
</P>
<P>
	A Coast Guard helicopter, two boats and a handful of people  
scoured the area in the dark, but found nothing. By the next 
morning, it looked like a false report, Hall said. 
</P>
<P>
	If there was a plane, radar failed to pick it up and nobody had  
reported a missing plane. It was later determined that nearby 
bluffs likely obscured radar during takeoff. 
</P>
<P>
	With no indication of an accident, Hall said, he suspended the  
search. 
</P>
<P>
	But it was renewed that night when the men failed to return the  
rented airplane and a missing persons report was filed with the 
Sheriff's Department. About the same time, the Coast Guard was told 
that somebody on the beach found an airplane seat cover. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the next 24 hours, the Coast Guard launched three boats and  
two helicopters, the local harbor master used his boat, and county 
and local police deployed two boats and two airplanes. 
</P>
<P>
	A piece of airplane insulation and a Walkman washed ashore on  
the third day. A severed foot in a shoe also was discovered on the 
beach. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was all we ever found,'' Hall said.  
</P>
<P>
	The operation was called off after three days, half a day longer  
than the Kennedy search. 
</P>
<P>
	But no recovery efforts followed, Ms. Lanni said.  
</P>
<P>
	``They don't look for wreckage when they feel it's beyond  
rescue,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the days after the near round-the-clock coverage of the  
search for Kennedy, Ms. Lanni said she asked herself: ``Can you 
believe what they're doing for him that they didn't do for Bob?'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the celebrity situation,'' she said, adding she  
understood the effort to find Kennedy. ``It's holding the public's 
attention. Even I'm scanning the TV set.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990725.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-25 19:40:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fiorentina Wins Gotham Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Gabriel Batistuta scored a pair of  
goals Sunday as Fiorentina defeated Aston Villa 4-0 in the finals 
of the Gotham Cup exhibition tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	Batistuta, the tournament's Most Outstanding Player, was  
supported by newcomer Predrag Mijatovic. Mijatovic had a goal, an 
assist and made a pass that set up a penalty kick by Batistuta. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was not surprised with how easily we won,'' Fiorentina coach  
Giovanni Trappatoni said through an interpreter. ``We have some of 
the best players in the world. I am very satisfied with the way we 
played.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rui Costa set up the first goal in the 19th minute when he  
threaded a diagonal lead pass to Mijatovic racing into the box from 
the left. The Serbian striker, who was acquired recently from Real 
Madrid, controlled the ball and placed a low shot just inside the 
far post. 
</P>
<P>
	Fiorentina made it 2-0 in the 36th minute on a penalty kick by  
Batistuta after Aston Villa defender Gareth Soughgate pulled him 
down in the box following a pass from Mijatovic. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mijatovic and Battistuta were the difference,'' said Aston  
Villa coach John Gregory. ``They taught us a lesson in finishing. 
They're forwards are the best in Europe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Batistuta tallied his second goal in the 48th minute when he ran  
onto a cross from Mijatovic on the right side and tucked a low shot 
inside the far post from 15 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	Costa then closed the scoring in the 87th minute running onto a  
long pass from Abel Balbo and slipping the ball into the net from 
close range with the outside of his right foot. 
</P>
<P>
	In the consolation match, Panathinaikos edged Ajox, 3-2.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
