<HEADLINE> New Pressures for Girls in Sports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In team sports, girls are where the growth is.  
But as competition increases, some coaches report girls' bad 
sportsmanship is increasing, too. 
</P>
<P>
	``The major growth in youth sports is the result of increased  
female participation,'' said Thomas B. Doyle, vice president of 
information and research for the National Sporting Goods 
Association. Between 1990 and 1998, the participation rates of 
girls rose faster than those of boys in almost every category, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	However, with the new opportunities in girls' athletics comes  
new pressure. Some coaches are reporting that girls, their parents 
and their fans are developing some of the same bad attitudes that 
have been notorious in boys' sports. 
</P>
<P>
	The NSGA, which looked at baseball, basketball, soccer, softball  
and volleyball, divided participants into two classes -- those ages 
7 to 11 and those ages 12 to 17. In almost every category, girls 
outpaced boys, the study found. 
</P>
<P>
	In baseball, for instance, participation among girls ages 7-11  
rose 20.5 percent to about 1.07 million who played least twice in a 
given year. In contrast, participation by boys fell 1.9 percent, 
although more boys -- about 4.7 million -- were on the field. 
</P>
<P>
	Among 12- to 17-year-old soccer players, girls' participation  
rose 17.6 percent to about 1.8 million, while boys' participation 
fell 3.2 percent to about 2.2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The faster rise among girls than boys is likely to continue a  
few years before it begins to slow, Doyle said. And even though 
girls trail in total participation, this only means that girls 
amount to a growth market. ``There is potentially a lot more young 
ladies that could enter team sports than the boys could,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gender equality has much to do with the jump, Doyle said.  
Federal Title IX requirements that schools divide their resources 
fairly are felt most strongly on the college and high school 
levels, he said. But this lets younger players, their parents and 
their coaches dream about athletic stardom. So the enhanced 
opportunities are creating interest in the elementary and 
recreational league levels, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pre-Title IX, there was almost a discouragement for girls to  
play,'' said Connee Zotos, athletics director at Drew University, 
Madison, N.J. The common attitude toward female athletes was 
``That's nice, dear,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	That's changed. With more girls and women competing, the  
pressure for a lead position or more playing time becomes more 
intense, Zotos said. And at the highest levels, such as NCAA 
Division I, ``It's a business,'' she said. ``You either produce 
or....'' 
</P>
<P>
	Those pressures filter down, said Zotos, who took part in April  
in a seminar, ``Screaming Parents, Sobbing Athletes,'' organized by 
the Women's Sports Foundation, a gender equality advocacy group. 
</P>
<P>
	Females are not as bad as males are -- at least, not yet, Zotos  
said. ``I'm hoping it never will be to that degree,'' she said. ``I 
hope women draw it back toward the middle.'' But she is hearing bad 
language in the stands and getting more pressure from parents on 
playing time, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	What this means is that females respond like males to the same  
athletic pressures, said Holly Gera, athletics director at New 
Jersey's Montclair State University. 
</P>
<P>
	Where the pressure is lower, the conduct often is better, Gera  
said. ``We've had some parents who were overzealous,'' she said. 
But at her school, where the fan base for women's sports is 
relatively small, things are under control, she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
