<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Power Outage on Rams First Workout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MACOMB, Ill. (AP) -- St. Louis Rams players had to dress in the  
dark because of a power outage for their first full-pad workout in 
104-degree weather Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The electricity went out at Western Illinois' Brophy Hall about  
2 p.m. -- about 1 1-2 hours before practice -- and it wasn't restored 
for more than three hours. Equipment manager Todd Hewitt borrowed 
two flashlights from campus police and a scented strawberry candle 
from the locker of defensive lineman Jeff Zgonina so he could issue 
equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	Players at first were hoping that practice might be cancelled.  
</P>
<P>
	``That's the first thing that crossed my mind,'' rookie safety  
Rich Coady said. ``I think that's the first thing that crosses 
anybody's mind when anything's not exactly like it should be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After those hopes were dashed, they got down to business. The  
only problem anyone had was linebacker Charlie Clemons forgot to 
put on his jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	Coady, a third-round pick out of Texas A&AMP;M, said he didn't  
really want to skip practice. Coach Dick Vermeil had already given 
players the morning off except for a special teams walkthrough. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm always looking at it as `Hey, we're going to have practice  
unless Coach Vermeil is having a great day or something and lets us 
off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vermeil wasn't about to do that. Temperatures have been above or  
near triple digits the first three days of camp, but so far he has 
made few concessions. On Saturday he switched a full-pad workout to 
shoulder pads and shorts, and on Sunday he cut the scheduled 2 
1-2-hour workout about 25 minutes short. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no way to run away from heat up here,'' Vermeil said.  
``You can't set the tone that every time it's hot we're going to do 
something to make it more comfortable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vermeil also pointed out that the Rams, who play home games in  
the air-conditioned Trans World Dome, might face heat in the third 
game of the season at Cincinnati Oct. 3. 
</P>
<P>
	``It could be muggier than hell,'' he said. ``We can't ask them  
to take the pads off.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990725.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-25 15:00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CBS Defends Its Record on Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- CBS has been more diligent than other  
networks in working to include minorities in its schedule, CBS 
executive Leslie Moonves said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The major broadcast networks have come under fire from the NAACP  
and others for fielding a nearly all-white lineup of new fall 
shows. CBS is not exempt from the criticism, with its new offerings 
largely devoid of color. 
</P>
<P>
	But Moonves, president and chief executive officer of CBS  
Television, said the network does feature ethnic characters in 12 
of its 19 fall series. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can, we will do more ... but CBS stands alone as the No. 1  
network aware of its responsibility in this area,'' Moonves told 
the summer meeting of the Television Critics Association. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS is the home of Cosby, Cheech Marin (``Nash Bridges''), Della  
Reese (``Touched by an Angel'') and others, Moonves said. 
</P>
<P>
	The network will meet with the NAACP within the next month to  
discuss the issue, Moonves said. 
</P>
<P>
	But CBS boasted Sunday about two new shows -- the fall series  
``Now and Again,'' which features black actor Dennis Haysbert as a 
scientist, and ``City of Angels,'' a midseason hospital drama with 
a predominantly black cast. 
</P>
<P>
	The latter, from veteran producer Steven Bochco (``Hill Street  
Blues,'' ``L.A. Law,'' ``NYPD Blue''), stars Vivica A. Fox, Blair 
Underwood and Michael Warren. 
</P>
<P>
	A major reason for doing the series was to use the many black  
actors, writers and directors who are ignored by the industry, 
Bochco said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's this extraordinary talent pool underutilized in our  
business, both in New York and Los Angeles,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Warren, who played police Officer Bobby Hill in ``Hill Street  
Blues,'' lamented television's lack of progress since a 
two-decade-old study on the lack of racial inclusiveness. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're asking the same question that was asked 22 years  
ago, something needs to be done,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bochco called the lack of minorities on TV a function of  
economics rather than racism. 
</P>
<P>
	If audiences fail to watch shows such as ``Paris,'' a drama  
Bochco produced a decade ago starring James Earl Jones, or the 
failed 1995 family drama ``Under One Roof,'' networks don't want to 
take the risk again, he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
