<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-25 17:50:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Turner Has 'Something To Prove' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FROSTBURG, Md. (AP) -- After the turmoil and excitement of the  
past two weeks, the three-hour drive to the Allegheny Mountains 
wasn't about to provide any kind of escape for the Washington 
Redskins. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a normal urgency, and then obviously there's a lot  
more,'' coach Norv Turner said Sunday as the first players reported 
to training camp. ``I think everyone who's with the Redskin 
organization has something to prove. I certainly feel like I do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Turner, who needs to make the playoffs this season to have a  
chance at keeping his job, is trying to get the focus on Xs and Os 
and practice schedules. That's not easy to do when new owner Daniel 
Snyder is shaking up the management and business side of things, 
firing more than two dozen employees and ousting Charley Casserly 
from the general manager's job. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one's been asking a lot about it,'' Turner said. ``But  
yeah, it's nice to get started on the football.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The fans making the annual pilgrimage to Frostburg are just as  
anxious about the man who spent $800 million for their favorite 
team. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm kind of nervous,'' said Pete Burke, from Syracuse, N.Y.,  
as he stood outside the players' dorm collecting autographs on a 
shirt. ``What's he going to do with everybody? He's got rid of all 
the people in the front office already.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About 47 players -- rookies, quarterbacks and players coming off  
injuries -- are eligible to practice starting Monday. The rest of 
the roster takes the field Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	If it's any consolation to Turner, the players are the most  
oblivious to the saga. All they've heard is that Snyder wants them 
to shape up and win. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't really keep up with it at all,'' fullback Larry Bowie  
said. ``I don't think it really affects me. The new owner has his 
opinion as to how he thinks the team should be. I think it'll have 
some effect as far as making some of the guys perform better or 
come out with a different attitude.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Distractions aside, there are plenty of practical football  
matters on Turner's plate. 
</P>
<P>
	His No. 1 priority over the next three days is getting new  
quarterback Brad Johnson in the flow. The Redskins gave up three 
draft picks for Johnson in February, but he missed most of the 
spring workouts because of knee surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	There is also the battle for the job of starting left tackle.  
Shar Pourdanesh and Joe Paten will get plenty of scrutiny right 
away, and the winner will get to challenge free-agent signee Andy 
Heck when he arrives Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Turner also has a rare Redskins luxury: His first-round draft  
choice isn't a holdout. If Champ Bailey can get a quick feel for 
the cornerback spot, Turner said he could foresee the No. 7 overall 
pick getting some snaps at receiver on opening day. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the newest face in Redskins management, Vinny  
Cerrato, will spend the next month or so shopping for more players. 
The Redskins have three first-round draft picks next year, giving 
Cerrato plenty of room to deal if he sees an obvious gap that needs 
filling. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will look into anything that will help upgrade the  
roster,'' said Cerrato, hired on Friday as Casserle's replacement 
and given the title of director of player personnel. ``Those draft 
picks are very valuable, so it would have be something very 
enticing.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
