<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Media Firm Buys Into NBA Mavericks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- The company that owns the Dallas Morning News  
announced plans to buy a minority interest in the Dallas Mavericks 
for $24 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The Belo Corp., which also own TV station WFAA, will own 12.38  
percent of the NBA team. A group headed by Ross Perot Jr. owns a 
majority stake in the Mavericks. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the deal, Belo obtained a 6.19 percent nonvoting  
interest in The Arena Group, the partnership formed by the 
Mavericks and the National Hockey League Dallas Stars to build and 
operate the new arena under construction in downtown Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal is subject to NBA approval, which is expected to take  
about a month. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are excited about the opportunity to have a relationship  
with the Dallas Mavericks and the NBA,'' said Robert W. Decherd, 
Belo's chairman, president and chief executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Major league sports are an important part of the fabric of  
this community. Belo's investment in the Mavericks enhances our 
participation in the immense popularity of professional sports in 
the Dallas-Fort Worth area, the company's largest market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harold Gaar, Belo's vice president for financial and investor  
relations, said the company will not take an active role in the 
management of the team or the arena. 
</P>
<P>
	The 12.38 percent stake was the interest retained by original  
Mavericks owner Donald Carter when he sold the team to Perot's 
group in 1996. Crescent Real Estate Co., owned by Fort Worth 
financier Richard Rainwater, bought the stake in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Belo, based in Dallas, also owns seven other daily newspapers  
and 16 other network TV stations. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
