<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Candidates Skeptical About Gambling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Bill Bradley calls it a threat to the poor.  
Pat Buchanan warns it can ruin families. Steve Forbes voted against 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	Polls find that most Americans favor legalized gambling. But  
most presidential candidates are skeptical, if not downright 
hostile, toward the proliferation of casinos, lotteries and other 
forms of state-sponsored or state-sanctioned betting. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans Forbes, Buchanan, Lamar Alexander and Texas Gov.  
George W. Bush, and Democrat Bradley, are among the candidates on 
the record criticizing gambling as a bad bet for American families, 
particularly young people and the poor. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican Sen. John McCain of Arizona may be the candidate  
friendliest to the gambling industry. He is a longtime defender of 
Indian tribal casinos and supported legislation in 1995 paving the 
way for gambling ``cruises to nowhere.'' Las Vegas casino 
executives Steve Wynn and J. Terrance Lanni have each given the 
maximum $1,000 to McCain's campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore has parked himself on middle ground  
between McCain and the gambling critics. Gore ``believes it is up 
to individual communities to make the decision about whether 
gambling should be legalized,'' his office said. 
</P>
<P>
	Because lotteries and casinos are run or regulated on the state  
level, gambling may never emerge as a major issue in federal 
campaigns. Thirty-seven states and the District of Columbia now run 
lotteries, while commercial casinos operate in 10 states and Indian 
tribes run casinos in at least 22 states. 
</P>
<P>
	A Gallup poll released last month found that nearly two-thirds  
of American adults approve of legal gambling, but that 55 percent 
of them believe it is creating ``a compulsive gambling problem in 
this country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, for one, seems to share that ambivalence.  
</P>
<P>
	He presides over a state lottery approved by Texas voters three  
years before he became governor. Bush himself, as a private 
citizen, voted in favor of creating the lottery, his office said. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet, Bush has made clear that he has qualms about gambling and  
would campaign and vote against the introduction of casinos if 
voters are presented with another ballot question. 
</P>
<P>
	``Casino gambling is not OK. It has ruined the lives of too many  
adults and it can do the same thing to our children,'' Bush 
declared in the report of his state Task Force on Illegal Gambling. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes, a New Jersey resident, says he voted against introducing  
casino gambling in Atlantic City in 1977. In a 1996 column panning 
proposals to allow video gambling on airplanes, the magazine 
publisher wrote: ``We have enough gambling opportunities on the 
ground. There ought to be a haven in the heavens from these 
temptations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander, as governor of Tennessee for eight years, opposed  
gambling except for bingo for charitable purposes. In 1980, he 
opposed legalizing pinball gambling as ``a consumer rip-off that 
preyed on the young and would have attracted organized crime to our 
state,'' according to campaign literature. 
</P>
<P>
	Among other Republican presidential hopefuls:  
</P>
<P>
	--Gary Bauer has called gambling ``an addictive blight'' and  
challenged other Republicans to turn down campaign contributions 
from gambling interests. 
</P>
<P>
	--At a 1995 rally in Iowa, Buchanan called legalized gambling ``a  
vice and an addiction ... destructive to the work ethic (and) 
ruinous to the family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch startled the gambling industry in 1997 by  
briefly proposing to close and ban any gambling establishment 
within 10,000 feet of where young people congregate, including 
schools. 
</P>
<P>
	--Former Vice President Dan Quayle ``has very serious concerns  
about the impact gambling has on the American family'' but 
ultimately believes the decision is up to individual states, his 
campaign says. 
</P>
<P>
	--Former American Red Cross president Elizabeth Dole said through  
a spokesman that gambling ``helps communities by creating tax 
revenues (but) also has human consequences that can lead to broken 
families and crime.'' The issue is one for states to sort out, she 
added. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Democratic side, Gore's hands-off approach to gambling  
contrasts with the views of his only challenger. As a senator from 
New Jersey, Bradley sponsored a 1987 law banning sports betting in 
the 46 states that did not then allow it. He told reporters in New 
Hampshire this year that if he were a governor, he would reject 
more gambling because it attracts and hurts low-income people. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
