<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Why Are Prairie Chickens Dying? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOLCOMB, Kan. (AP) -- They are known affectionately as the  
``Chicken Boys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Their mission is to find out why the population of lesser  
prairie chickens is declining on the grasslands of southwest 
Kansas. 
</P>
<P>
	Although their nickname and the subject of their study might  
sound humorous, diminishing numbers of the bird may be a warning 
that its habitat is in trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the canary in the mine. If we lose the prairie chicken,  
it's an indication that the prairie isn't healthy,'' said Brent 
Jamison, one of three researchers conducting a study sponsored by 
Kansas State University and the Kansas Department of Wildlife and 
Parks. 
</P>
<P>
	Although there are no exact figures on the number of lesser  
prairie chickens in Kansas, surveys show the population has 
declined since the 1960s throughout its habitat. 
</P>
<P>
	The lesser prairie chicken, which actually is a small grouse  
with brown and white stripes, lives in Colorado, Kansas, New 
Mexico, Oklahoma and Texas. Kansas and Texas still have hunting 
seasons for the bird, but the other three states have closed their 
seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	For the past three years, researchers have been studying the  
bird's habitat on 14,400 acres of the Sunflower Electric Power 
Corp.'s plant site in Holcomb. The site includes the sand sagebrush 
prairie that the lesser prairie chicken favors for nesting. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers have trapped 293 birds and have placed radio collars  
on about 160. They now are tracking the movements of 60 birds that 
have been collared this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers point to the conversion of the prairie to  
cropland as the biggest reason for the demise of the lesser prairie 
chicken. 
</P>
<P>
	This process has occurred largely during the past 50 years,  
Jamison said, and accelerated during the 1960s with the rise of 
center-pivot irrigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Moreover, lesser prairie chickens do not seem to adapt to  
cropland. Of approximately 70 nests found in the Kansas study, only 
one was in a crop field. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet loss of habitat appears to be only one piece of the puzzle.  
</P>
<P>
	Researcher Tom Walker said the bird's numbers have continued to  
decline in recent years despite the fact that grassland no longer 
is being converted to cropland. 
</P>
<P>
	Another factor in the decline of the lesser prairie chicken is  
the bird's susceptibility to predators, particularly as chicks. 
</P>
<P>
	Jamison said about half of all chicks are eaten by such  
predators as snakes, coyotes, skunks and hawks. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're the McDonald's of the prairie. Everything eats them,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Overgrazing poses a problem for the bird's habitat in other  
states, Jamison said, but it does not appear to be troublesome in 
Kansas. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers plan to complete their study in August and publish  
their results. A new three-year study scheduled to start next 
spring will seek to develop land management strategies to preserve 
the habitat of the prairie chicken. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, the Biodiversity Legal Foundation, based in Boulder,  
Colo., petitioned the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service to list the 
lesser prairie chicken as a threatened species. Last year, the 
federal agency made the bird a candidate for future listing. 
</P>
<P>
	``The biology tells us that the bird is in serious enough shape  
that it does warrant listing as threatened, but there are more 
species that need help first,'' said Erich Langer, outreach 
coordinator for the agency's field office in Tulsa, Okla. 
</P>
<P>
	Finding a way to keep the bird off the list is one of the goals  
of the Kansas research. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a new way of dealing with things. What we're trying to do  
is jump in and be proactive,'' said Roger Applegate, who is 
coordinating the studies for the Kansas Department of Wildlife and 
Parks. 
</P>
<P>
	Naming the lesser prairie chicken a threatened species most  
likely would ban hunting of the bird. Colorado, New Mexico and 
Oklahoma already have closed their hunting seasons, and Jamison 
said extending this ban to Kansas would alienate a group of the 
bird's supporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Jamison noted that an excise tax on sporting guns and ammunition  
helped pay for the first Kansas study, and Applegate said it also 
will help fund the second study. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hunting is not the cause of the decline,'' said Curran Salter,  
another researcher working on the study. 
</P>
<P>
	Applegate agreed, noting that Colorado has experienced  
population declines even though it banned hunting of the bird 
decades ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Extinction also would be a blow to bird watchers, who enjoy  
observing the lesser prairie chicken's colorful courtship ritual 
each spring. 
</P>
<P>
	The males gather at breeding grounds where they strut and leap  
to gain the attention of prospective mates. The male courtship 
ritual also includes inflating their pink throat sacs and emitting 
loud noises, which explains why breeding areas often are called 
booming grounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every spring, people come from all over the world,'' said  
Jasper Carlton, executive director of the Biodiversity Legal 
Foundation. ``What I fear is that they are coming to see the last 
ones.'' 
</P>
<P>
	State and federal wildlife officials say they are doing  
everything they can to prevent that from happening. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service's field office in Manhattan  
recently received $75,000 to encourage landowners to enter into 
voluntary agreements to help restore the bird's habitat. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Gill, field supervisor for the Ecological Services Division  
at the Manhattan office, said many landowners have expressed 
interest in the program, although no agreements have been signed. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Williams, secretary of the Kansas Department of Wildlife  
and Parks, said he is optimistic about the bird's ability to bounce 
back. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the prospects are good,'' he said. ``The species has a  
lot of attention now. Partnerships are being created between states 
and landowners.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
