<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Telecom Firm Selling Hawaii Assets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONOLULU (AP) -- After spending tens of millions of dollars to  
build a sophisticated fiber-optic network connecting Hawaii's six 
largest islands, GST Telecommunications Inc. has announced plans to 
pull out of the state. 
</P>
<P>
	The Vancouver, Wash.-based company said Friday it is soliciting  
offers for its main Hawaii assets. Industry experts have identified 
AT&AMP;T Corp. and Sprint Corp. as potential buyers. 
</P>
<P>
	GST and Oceanic Communications are the only companies that use  
their own wire-based networks to compete with GTE Hawaiian Tel, the 
state's dominant carrier. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the inter-island network, GST provides phone  
service to local businesses and operates an Internet service 
provider, GST Hawaii OnLine. 
</P>
<P>
	Company spokesman Steve Kuyatt said it is not known whether the  
online operation will be included in the sale. 
</P>
<P>
	Kuyatt said GST's Hawaii pullout is part of a strategic decision  
to concentrate on its core market, the Western United States. As 
part of the strategy, GST also is selling its telecommunications 
operations on Guam for undisclosed amounts. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprint is buying GST's equipment network on Guam and Startec  
Global Communications Corp. is acquiring GST's customer base there. 
</P>
<P>
	GST's decision to leave Hawaii surprised industry officials  
because of the company's extensive investments in the state. In 
late 1996, GST's then-president, John Warta, said the company 
intended to spend $49 million to $54 million over the next two 
years to build its inter-island fiber network. Kuyatt said Thursday 
that the projections weren't off the mark, but declined to give 
specific figures. 
</P>
<P>
	Warta, a key proponent of GST's push into the Hawaii market,  
left the company last year. 
</P>
<P>
	GST had plans to eventually go head-to-head with Hawaiian Tel in  
business and residential markets. Over the past two years GST had 
been slowly building its land-based network on Oahu and Maui, but 
had not launched residential service. 
</P>
<P>
	The 4-year-old company sells integrated communications services  
to small and medium-sized businesses in seven other states: 
Washington, Oregon, California, Idaho, Arizona, New Mexico and 
Texas. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
