<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Thunderstorms spread across the South and rolled through the  
north-central states on Sunday. Storm warnings were issued for 
parts of New England. 
</P>
<P>
	Low pressure sitting over the Southeast produced a dense area of  
strong storms from southern Alabama into southern Georgia and 
northern Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Showers and occasional thunderstorms also were scattered over  
parts of Arkansas, Louisiana, Mississippi, central Florida and the 
coast of South Carolina. Scattered showers developed in southern 
Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	In the North, a ribbon of strong thunderstorms and locally heavy  
showers rolled across the Dakotas and into northern Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	Hail up to 1.75 inches in diameter was reported in parts of  
North Dakota, and tornado watches were posted for northeastern 
South Dakota, southeastern North Dakota and northwestern Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	A few showers and thunderstorms also stretched into Nebraska.  
</P>
<P>
	Some of that rain was expected to reach Wisconsin and Michigan  
during the night. 
</P>
<P>
	Another area of low pressure produced scattered thunderstorms  
over the Northeast, from Pennsylvania and New York state across New 
England into northern Maine. 
</P>
<P>
	Severe thunderstorm warnings were issued for parts of eastern  
Massachusetts, and hail as big as golf balls was reported in New 
Hampshire. 
</P>
<P>
	As moist air streamed across the Southwest, showers and  
occasional thunderstorms also developed during the afternoon across 
parts of Arizona, New Mexico and Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	More rain was possible in parts of Wyoming, Idaho and Montana.  
</P>
<P>
	Sunday's temperatures around the Lower 48 states ranged from a  
morning low of 33 at Stanley, Idaho, to a midday reading of 99 at 
Little Rock, Ark. The lowest wind chill was 28 at Mullan Pass, 
Idaho, and the highest heat index by midday was 113 at Little Rock. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
