<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rescue Efforts in 2 Other Crashes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Timelines for the rescue and recovery efforts for two downed  
pilots -- one in Northern California, one in Southern California: 
</P>
<P>
	Ron Trenton crash:  
</P>
<P>
	Feb. 11, 1997 -- Ron Trenton flies 35 miles from San Diego to  
Santa Catalina Island and begins return flight at about 3 p.m. At 
3:19, his plane disappears from radar. First word of his 
disappearance goes out at 8:35 p.m. when a friend tells authorities 
Trenton's plane is overdue. At 8:45 p.m., Coast Guard launches 
first helicopter followed by several boats. The air search is 
suspended at 2:30 a.m. until first light, but boats keep working 
through the night. 
</P>
<P>
	Feb. 12, 1997 -- 2,000-square-mile search area is narrowed to 100  
square miles. Four Coast Guard helicopters, six airplanes and five 
boats saturate the area. The Navy lends two ships in the area to 
the rescue effort. 
</P>
<P>
	Feb. 13, 1997 -- Coast Guard talks to family about ending search.  
Holding out hope, the Trenton family asks that the search continue. 
</P>
<P>
	Feb. 14, 1997 -- Coast Guard continues search, investigates  
report of an oil sheen on the surface of ocean that turns out to be 
false. 
</P>
<P>
	Feb. 15, 1997 -- Search for Trenton ends.  

</P>
<P>
	Robert Beach Crash:  
</P>
<P>
	May 22, 1998 -- Robert Beach takes off from Half Moon Bay at  
about 9 p.m. Twelve minutes later, witnesses report seeing two 
white lights spinning into the ocean or hearing a loud splash. 
Coast Guard sends emergency broadcast to area boaters and pilots to 
look out for survivors and debris at 9:18 p.m., launches helicopter 
and boats at 9:19. Air search suspended for the night at 1:30 a.m., 
but boats continue patrol. 
</P>
<P>
	May 23, 1998 -- Unable to confirm crash, Coast Guard suspends  
search at 7:37 a.m. Resumes at 11:15 p.m. after missing person's 
report is filed and debris reported recovered on beach. Coast Guard 
launches three boats and two helicopters, the local harbor master 
uses his boat and county and local police deploy two airplanes to 
search for the men. 
</P>
<P>
	May 24, 1998 -- Airplane insulation and a Walkman are washed  
ashore and a severed foot in a shoe is also found on the beach. 
Coast Guard continues to search into the night. 
</P>
<P>
	May 25, 1998 -- After talking with Beach's family, the Coast  
Guard ends the search, assuming the pilot is dead. 
</P>
<P>
	----	 
</P>
<P>
	Source: Interviews and Coast Guard and NTSB records.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990725.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-25 12:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Disorientation Eyed As Crash Cause </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AQUINNAH, Mass. (AP) -- It's nearly impossible for a non-pilot to  
understand the phenomenon of spatial disorientation, so confusing 
to aviators that some have flown nearly upside down for miles 
without realizing it. 
</P>
<P>
	The closest civilian sensation is Walt Disney World's Space  
Mountain roller coaster, said James Davidson, a pilot and president 
of ATC Flight Training Center in Fort Washington, Md. 
</P>
<P>
	``You are going very fast through pitch-dark tunnels and you  
can't tell what direction you're going,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Another comparison, he said, is the sensation of lying on a bed  
after drinking too much alcohol. The room spins around, and one 
must put a hand on a wall to steady oneself. 
</P>
<P>
	Spatial disorientation occurs when a pilot loses the horizon,  
and conditions were ripe for such a phenomenon during the last 
flight of John F. Kennedy Jr. 
</P>
<P>
	It was night, he was flying over the sea, there were no land  
lights to guide him, it was hazy and there was no moon -- perfect 
conditions for the sky and the ocean to blend into a dark tunnel 
with no boundaries. 
</P>
<P>
	Spatial disorientation is blamed for more than 90 percent of  
inexperienced pilot crashes, and it is being examined as a possible 
cause of the July 16 crash that killed Kennedy, his wife, Carolyn 
Bessette Kennedy, and her sister, Lauren Bessette, off the coast of 
Martha's Vineyard. 
</P>
<P>
	In the absence of radio transmissions from Kennedy, the cause of  
the crash may never be conclusively known. 
</P>
<P>
	But pilots around the country say the combination of Kennedy's  
inexperience -- he was qualified only to fly visually and not using 
instruments -- and the poor visibility over the Atlantic that night 
points to a classic case of spatial disorientation. 
</P>
<P>
	Radar painted a fairly definitive picture of Kennedy's flight  
from Fairfield, N.J., to Martha's Vineyard aboard his single-engine 
Piper Saratoga. 
</P>
<P>
	His takeoff and the first leg of his flight along Long Island  
Sound apparently were uneventful. 
</P>
<P>
	But as the plane left behind the lights of Westerly, R.I., it  
entered an area where other pilots who were in the air that night 
said the horizon was extremely difficult to detect. 
</P>
<P>
	About 34 miles west of the Martha's Vineyard airport at West  
Tisbury, Kennedy's plane began a slightly fast, but still normal, 
descent of 700 feet per minute, eventually going from 5,600 feet 
above sea level to 2,300 feet in five minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	About 20 miles from the airport, he banked toward the right and  
climbed to 2,600 feet, perhaps just as added insurance to make sure 
he was fully set for his approach, or perhaps because he was having 
trouble with the horizon. 
</P>
<P>
	He flew at that altitude for about a minute.  
</P>
<P>
	It is unclear from official reports if he then began descending  
again, but at about 17 miles from West Tisbury, he took a sudden 
right turn, away from the airport, and the plane began dropping at 
the hazardous rate of 5,000 feet per minute. 
</P>
<P>
	It was in that maneuver, aviation experts speculate, that  
Kennedy exhibited signs of spatial disorientation, putting the 
plane into a dive as he tried to right himself. 
</P>
<P>
	In spatial disorientation, a pilot can actually be in a dive and  
believe he is flying level. 
</P>
<P>
	This may have been an ``unfeelable bank,'' said William  
Langewiesche, a pilot with 15,000 cockpit hours, in which Kennedy 
might not have known if his craft were pointed toward sea or sky. 
</P>
<P>
	And a plane, unlike a car, does not easily compensate.  
</P>
<P>
	``A plane is not directionally stable,'' said Langewiesche,  
author of ``Inside the Sky: A Meditation on Flight.'' ``Whatever 
the reason that you went into a bank is precisely the reason you 
won't come out of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kennedy was considered a conscientious pilot who witnesses said  
never intended to fly at night, but he also was in a dangerous 
category -- having only logged between 100 and 200 hours of flight 
time. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a time when you think you are better than you are,''  
Davidson said. 
</P>
<P>
	``An experienced pilot would never have gotten into this  
situation,'' Langewiesche said. ``(Kennedy) was a babe in the 
woods.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
