<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EPA Focuses on Foul Ferries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- John Durand of Bainbridge Island, Wash., loves  
his daily commute across Puget Sound, where ferry boats cut the 
crisp sea air and offer stunning views of Mount Rainier and 
Seattle's skyline. 
</P>
<P>
	``It can be absolutely gorgeous,'' says Durand, a 36-year-old  
manager at a computer software company. ``It's actually a nice way 
to get to work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But a study released this month discloses a darker side of the  
boats that carry millions of passengers in California, Washington, 
Alaska and 32 other states. 
</P>
<P>
	Bluewater Network, a San Francisco-based environmental group,  
says ferries are 10 times more polluting per passenger than 
automobiles and nearly 13 times more polluting than buses. 
</P>
<P>
	While questioned by some, the study has raised eyebrows among  
environmentalists and ferry buffs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Environmental Protection Agency also has turned its  
regulatory eye on ferries and other commercial boats. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the 1990 Clean Air Act, the EPA is supposed to complete a  
rule in November that for the first time will regulate emissions 
from diesel-powered marine engines. 
</P>
<P>
	The rule, to take effect in 2006, would allow 7.2 grams per  
kilowatt hour of exhaust emissions that contribute to ozone -- down 
nearly 50 percent from the 13.3 grams per hour the engines now 
emit. 
</P>
<P>
	Many ferry riders are aware of the black smoke that comes from  
ferry smokestacks but assume the vessels are good for the 
environment on the whole because they carry hundreds of people who 
otherwise might drive cars. 
</P>
<P>
	The study highlights a trend among environmental groups  
increasingly focusing public attention on the down side of 
unconventional modes of transportation such as personal 
water-craft, snowmobiles and all-terrain vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	Ferries ``may have gotten a free pass'' as environmental groups  
looked at pollution resulting from cars and sport utility vehicles, 
said Eric Goldstein, a lawyer for the Natural Resources Defense 
Council in New York City. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ferry engines may deserve scrutiny,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Bluewater Network used emission and ridership data for cars,  
buses and a popular ferry route in San Francisco to conclude that 
diesel buses emit pollutants of 0.63 grams per passenger mile, cars 
emit 0.80 grams per passenger mile, and diesel ferries emit 7.90 
grams per passenger mile. 
</P>
<P>
	Russell Long, the group's executive director, said that while he  
expected ferries to pollute more than buses or cars, he was shocked 
by the extent of the difference -- and a little saddened. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a shame we have to deromanticize the ferry as a result of  
this,'' he said. ``They're an elegant way to travel to and from 
work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ferries carry 100 million passengers each year in 35 states,  
according to the International Marine Transit Association, a ferry 
group in Hingham, Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	Bridges and cars put many ferries out of business earlier this  
century, but the boats have been getting more popular in recent 
years due to gridlock, new waterfront developments and ``fast 
ferries'' that can travel more than 30 mph, said Martha Reardon, 
secretary-treasurer of the ferry group. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is very much of a revival,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	Russell Hancock, vice president of the Bay Area Council, a  
business group that wants to add 120 fast ferries in San Francisco, 
said marine engines are dirty because it takes far more horsepower 
to move a ferry through choppy waters than it does to push a bus on 
wheels along a smooth road. 
</P>
<P>
	But Hancock contends Bluewater overstated the size of some  
ferries in the San Francisco plan and understated the amount of 
time cars will spend gridlocked in coming years. Increasing traffic 
means cumulative car emissions will escalate, he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
