<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GM Offers Buyouts to Thousands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Under pressure to cut costs, General Motors Corp.  
has offered thousands of salaried workers buyouts or early 
retirement plans. 
</P>
<P>
	Estimates on the number of offers range from about 3,000 to  
8,000, the Detroit Free Press reported Saturday. GM won't say 
exactly how many letters are going out or what percentage of the 
voluntary plans it expects will be accepted. The company has about 
48,000 U.S. salaried workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The company has been targeted by Wall Street analysts who say it  
has too much overhead in comparison with other automakers. Ford 
Motor Co. offered buyouts to an estimated 2,000 or more salaried 
employees last year. 
</P>
<P>
	GM has reduced its salaried ranks in the United States over the  
last couple of years, from about 49,720 at the end of 1997 to just 
fewer than 49,000 at the end of '98, according to spokeswoman 
Charlotte Grim. 
</P>
<P>
	GM has about 148,000 hourly workers in the United States, down  
from about 160,000 at the end of 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The Free Press said buyouts began in April, and most if not all  
the recipients are thought to be 50 or older. 
</P>
<P>
	Citing an unnamed employee, the newspaper said a 58-year-old  
employee is offered 74 percent of his or her salary per month until 
age 62. At that point, the monthly amount would go down to reflect 
monthly payments from Social Security. So the employee would get 
most of what he or she would have received if retiring at age 62. 
</P>
<P>
	Buyout offers for younger GM employees are less generous,  
granting about 15 months of pay, plus job placement counseling. 
They also would have a retirement benefit they could start 
collecting at age 62, the Free Press reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The company would not give details of the offers or reveal what  
percentage were buyout packages versus early retirements. 
</P>
<P>
	An investment analyst seemed generally pleased with the news.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's something companies do every now and then to try to  
reduce costs,'' said Jim Hall, in the Southfield office of 
California-based AutoPacific Inc. ``And it's tough to always ask 
the hourly ranks to lower their head count if you're not doing 
anything on the salaried level.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Contract talks with the United Auto Workers started last month.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
