<DOCNO> APW19990725.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-25 13:40:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stayner Family Victim of Kidnapping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MERCED, Calif. (AP) -- The FBI's suspect in the killing of a  
woman at Yosemite National Park has links to a 1970s kidnapping 
that remains one of California's most notorious crimes. 
</P>
<P>
	Murder suspect Cary Stayner is a brother of Steven Stayner, who  
in 1972 was snatched off a Merced street and remained missing for 
seven years. 
</P>
<P>
	Steven Stayner was reunited with his family in 1980. But as if  
he lived his short life under a cloud, he died in 1989 in a 
collision with a hit-and-run driver at 24. A television miniseries 
later portrayed the saga of his abduction. 
</P>
<P>
	It was as if Stayner's life was split in three -- his early years  
growing up in a working-class family of seven, his lost years with 
kidnapper Kenneth Parnell and the time back with his family. 
</P>
<P>
	Parnell kept his hold on Stayner by showering him with gifts and  
telling him his parents could no longer afford him. 
</P>
<P>
	Their years together ended when the teen-ager went to police  
with a freshly kidnapped 8-year-old boy. Steven said he didn't want 
the younger boy to suffer the same abuse. 
</P>
<P>
	He was initially riddled with guilt about turning in his  
abductor and then angry about his lost family. 
</P>
<P>
	A fitful student, the resurrected Stayner juggled book offers,  
young love and a slew of traffic citations. He married and fathered 
two children before meeting his tragic end while driving a 
motorcycle on a suspended license. 
</P>
<P>
	Steven's siblings ranged from age 4 to 12 when he was kidnapped  
and lived their own ordeal. 
</P>
<P>
	``When Steve came home, everybody else all got shoved in the  
background and here's this hero,'' said his mother, Kay. 
</P>
<P>
	Stayner's sister, Jody, told mourners at his funeral that Steven  
``brought our broken-hearted family together.'' But his minister 
said the family felt like it had to share him with a curious 
nation. 
</P>
<P>
	When Steven died, Mrs. Stayner said she felt like her son had  
been ``loaned to us.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
