<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Raiders' Allen Gets Over Injury </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *With AP Photo    	
</P>
<P>
	NAPA, Calif. (AP) -- With Albert Lewis now retired, Eric Allen  
was asked if he was comfortable in assuming the role of elder 
statesman for the Oakland Raiders' secondary. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yeah, I guess so,'' he said with a smile Sunday after the  
Raiders' second day of training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	Allen, a 12-year-veteran and an unquestionable leader, comes off  
of knee surgery and is eager to join a cornerback staff that 
includes former Heisman Trophy winner Charles Woodson and offseason 
acquisition Darrien Gordon. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's sort of like everything is new again. It's like your  
rookie year,'' he said. ``Everything is the first time for me since 
the knee injury. You have to get back your timing, your confidence 
in your knee. But I feel good. I think everything is progressing 
pretty well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Allen, 33, tore his left anterior cruciate ligament on an  
interception return at Seattle on Nov. 15. Before his departure, 
the Raiders were 7-2. After it, they were 1-6. 
</P>
<P>
	His fellow defensive backs were also plagued by injuries. Free  
safety Eric Turner hurt his foot, while strong safety Anthony 
Newman was bothered by ankle and toe troubles. 
</P>
<P>
	Woodson, eventually named the league's Defensive Rookie of the  
Year, was the only starter to appear in all 16 games last season. 
</P>
<P>
	Linebacker Greg Biekert was looking forward to having everyone  
healthy again. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're ready to get going again,'' Biekert said. ``It's been a  
while since we've had both Erics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Intense but good-natured, Allen is already proving on the  
practice field that he's back in playing shape. On Saturday, he 
made two interceptions. 
</P>
<P>
	Because he needs to test his knee and some of the younger guys  
need field time, however, he's easing back into it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think they're letting me be flexible. It depends how I feel:  
if I feel I want to push it, if I want to back off and need some 
time,'' he said. ``It's kind of a gray area for me, and they're 
allowing me to go at my own pace. They know I'm not going to cheat 
myself. If anything, they're going to have to hold me back a little 
bit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Jon Gruden said Allen has more than proven how effective  
he can be when healthy. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's made great progress and we see real good signs for his  
return to full health,'' Gruden said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis, a 16-year veteran, moved from cornerback to safety last  
season. He made the transition successfully, grabbing his first 
career interception return for a touchdown. 
</P>
<P>
	At 38, Lewis decided to call it quits in the offseason. His  
presence as a gentleman and a leader in the locker room will be 
missed, but Allen is more than capable of taking the reins. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're never going to have the same chemistry when guys  
leave,'' Allen said. ``But the things you can do and accomplish can 
be the same.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
