<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gas Prices Jump More Than 5 Cents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMARILLO, Calif. (AP) -- Gasoline prices jumped about 5 cents in  
the past two weeks, spurred by higher crude oil prices and 
increased demand caused by recovering world economies, according to 
an industry analyst. 
</P>
<P>
	The national weighted average on Friday, including all grades  
and taxes, was $1.2671, up 5.18 cents from the previous survey 
conducted July 9, said Trilby Lundberg, publisher of the Lundberg 
Survey of 10,000 gas stations nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	It is the highest price in more than 18 months and the biggest  
hike nationally since late March, Ms. Lundberg said Sunday. This 
comes after prices dropped significantly between early May and 
early June. 
</P>
<P>
	Pump prices are high compared to last year, but are comparable  
with prices in 1996 and 1997 during the same period, Ms. Lundberg 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	She blamed the price hikes on production cuts by the  
Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries, as well as 
recovering Asian and Latin American economies that now require more 
energy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Globally, there's just a tighter balance between supply and  
demand,'' Ms. Lundberg said. 
</P>
<P>
	Pump prices were rising throughout the country but were most  
dramatic in the West, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	At self-service pumps, the average for regular unleaded was  
$1.2108, mid-grade was $1.3107 and premium was $1.3956. 
</P>
<P>
	For full-service, regular was $1.5449, mid-grade averaged  
$1.6330 and premium $1.7071. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
