<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Martin Agronsky    	
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Longtime television commentator Martin  
Agronsky, a voice from radio's golden age who created the ``talking 
heads'' television news format, died Sunday of congestive heart 
failure. He was 84. 
</P>
<P>
	Agronsky began in newspaper journalism, became a war  
correspondent on radio and was a Washington correspondent, foreign 
correspondent and commentator for U.S. television from 1943 until 
he retired in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	Agronsky's syndicated television program, ``Agronsky &AMP;  
Company,'' ended in early 1988 after an 18-year run. It was the 
nation's top-ranked public affairs program when Agronsky retired. 
</P>
<P>
	The show, which began as a newscast on Washington's WTOP-TV, now  
WUSA-TV, was considered the first to use the informal format of 
reporters talking among themselves rather than interviewing 
newsmakers. The format, generally with newsmakers participating, 
became the stock-in-trade of today's Sunday talk shows. 
</P>
<P>
	``Agronsky &AMP; Company'' ran less than a year as a local newscast,  
but the concept was spun off into a program syndicated on 
commercial and public television stations across the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Agronsky's first job was in 1936 as general assignment reporter  
for the Palestine Post, now the Jerusalem Post. Before he retired, 
he had worked for all three major networks and PBS, generally in 
high-profile positions. 

</P>
<P>
 *William Targ    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- William Targ, a former editor who agreed to  
publish Mario Puzo's ``The Godfather'' sight unseen, died Thursday. 
He was 92. 
</P>
<P>
	Targ worked for G.P. Putnam's Sons. He retired in 1978.  
</P>
<P>
	He worked with Simone de Beauvoir, Ashley Montagu and Lin  
Yutang, among others. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1968, Targ bought ``The Godfather'' for a $5,000 advance on  
the strength of an oral presentation. Two other publishers had 
already turned down the work, which went on to become the most 
profitable novel published by Putnam. 
</P>
<P>
	Targ, born in Chicago to parents who had emigrated from Russia,  
dropped out of high school after losing interest in all courses but 
English and print shop, in which he learned to set type by hand. He 
bought books second hand because he refused to borrow from 
libraries. 
</P>
<P>
	At age 22, he opened his own book shop and began piecing  
together what would become a collection of thousands of rare books. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990725.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-25 15:40:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Browns' Pres. Denies Cap Violation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEREA, Ohio (AP) -- Cleveland Browns president Carmen Policy said  
he is cooperating fully with the NFL and is innocent of any 
wrongdoing concerning charges the San Francisco 49ers violated the 
salary cap while under his control. 
</P>
<P>
	Policy and Dwight Clark, the Browns director of football  
operations who followed Policy from San Francisco, came under 
investigation by the league earlier in the week. 
</P>
<P>
	Last Thursday, the 49ers issued a statement saying the NFL was  
looking into the case of a player contract during the time when 
Policy was the team's president and Clark was general manager. 
</P>
<P>
	The player is reportedly tight end Brent Jones.  
</P>
<P>
	When asked if he was involved in any under-the-table payments to  
Jones, Policy said, ``No. No. No. Exclamation point. No. But I 
don't even think that is what is alleged.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Policy had deferred comment on the allegations until Sunday when  
he and Cleveland owner Al Lerner met with reporters during the 
Browns' afternoon practice. 
</P>
<P>
	``Stories about the 49ers and the cap have existed since the cap  
was created,'' Policy said. ``I think it's a situation that the 
league is looking at a fact pattern and we're cooperating. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've already cooperated with them early and we're cooperating  
further. I think it will turn out to be a situation that is not 
reflective of any kind of violation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The league was provided information by 49ers owner Denise  
DeBartolo York and her husband, John York, who continue to squabble 
with Eddie DeBartolo for control of the franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	Policy faces a maximum $250,000 fine if found guilty of any  
salary cap infractions. The 49ers could be fined $2 million and 
could lose future draft picks. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
