<DOCNO> APW19990725.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-25 23:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Seeks $1B for Veterans' Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration is asking Congress  
to add $1 billion in spending for veterans' health programs in the 
budget year that begins Oct. 1, Vice President Al Gore said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore set the announcement at Nashville International Airport as  
the kickoff of a day of appearances in his native Tennessee that 
included both official chores and a fund-raising reception for his 
2000 presidential campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House budget office was forwarding the request in a  
letter to Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	In prepared remarks, Gore said the $1 billion includes $800  
million to hire more medical workers ``and take other steps 
necessary to reduce waiting time and ensure quality care'' at 
Department of Veterans Affairs facilities; $100 million for home- 
and community based long-term care services and $100 million to 
help ``upgrade outdated and decaying facilities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore said the additional spending could be paid for under the  
administration's current budget request. He noted that he had 
served in Vietnam, where he was an Army journalist, and co-founded 
the Vietnam-era veterans caucus in Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement comes several days after Sen. Paul Wellstone,  
D-Minn., said a survey by his office found that 20 of the 22 VA 
health care networks would have spending shortfalls under the 
administration's $17.3 billion veterans health request for 2000. 
Veterans groups, citing the millions of World War II and Korean 
veterans at or approaching old age, have estimated the spending gap 
at $3 billion. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
