<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	U.S. Seeks $1B for Veterans' Plan  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration is asking Congress  
to add $1 billion in spending for veterans' health programs in the 
budget year that begins Oct. 1, Vice President Al Gore said Monday. 
Gore set the announcement at Nashville International Airport as the 
kickoff of a day of appearances in his native Tennessee that 
included both official chores and a fund-raising reception for his 
2000 presidential campaign. The White House budget office was 
forwarding the request in a letter to Congress. 

</P>
<P>
	Russian Cargo Plane Crashes  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- A Russian military plane with seven crew members  
on board crashed shortly after take-off from the Siberian city of 
Irkutsk on Monday, the Emergency Situations Ministry said. There 
was no immediate word on casualties, but rescue teams were at the 
crash site searching for survivors, according to the Federal 
Aviation Service. The plane, with 30 tons of cargo on board, went 
down just after departing from Irkutsk, and was headed to Perm in 
the Ural Mountains, officials said. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO, UN Try To Rebuild Confidence  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Despite efforts by NATO and the  
United Nations to bolster confidence in their ability to provide 
security in Kosovo, many Serbs remain skeptical and even fear for 
their lives. A meeting of the new transitional government committee 
of ethnic Albanians and Serbs, scheduled for Monday, was postponed 
after Serbs requested a delay to prepare for the funeral of 14 Serb 
farmers. The farmers were killed in a wheat field near the central 
Kosovo village of Gracko on Friday -- a display of violence that has 
put the U.N. goal of a peaceful, multiethnic Kosovo in jeopardy. 

</P>
<P>
	Wreckage Found in Colombia Plane Crash  
</P>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- The U.S. Army said wreckage spotted  
Sunday on a mountainside in southwestern Colombia might be that of 
an American spy plane that disappeared while on a counternarcotics 
mission over rebel-dominated territory. U.S. officials say the 
plane was on a routine mission over an area where drug crops are 
grown when it disappeared Saturday from radar screens. Its 
disappearance, however, was likely to heighten speculation in 
Colombia that Washington is getting deeply involved in the 
country's 35-year civil war. 

</P>
<P>
	Maintenance Man Arrested in Yosemite Murder  
</P>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- The FBI said a hotel maintenance man  
arrested in the beheading of a naturalist at Yosemite National Park 
is expected to be arraigned Monday. Cary Stayner, 37, was accused 
of killing Joie Ruth Armstrong, 26, whose decapitated body was 
found near her Yosemite housing on Thursday. Stayner, who is also a 
suspect in the killings of three park sightseers earlier this year, 
was arrested Saturday. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S.-China Relations Improving  
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE (AP) -- The United States and China remained at odds on  
NATO's bombing of the Chinese embassy in Belgrade but showed signs 
Sunday that their tattered relations might be on the mend. They 
also agreed the Taiwan crisis must be solved quickly. After a lunch 
meeting with the Chinese foreign minister, Secretary of State 
Madeleine Albright cited an ``easing of tensions'' and ``the 
restoration of communication over a very friendly lunch.'' Clearly, 
the Taiwan question remained touchy, although Albright said efforts 
by Taiwan's president to explain his provocative statements 
suggesting sovereignty ``thus far don't quite do it,'' and both she 
and Tang urged a peaceful resolution. 

</P>
<P>
	Woodstock '99 Bonfires Out of Hand  
</P>
<P>
	ROME, N.Y. (AP) -- A number of the bonfires on the Woodstock '99  
grounds got out of hand Sunday night and raged into a three-alarm 
blaze near the concert's main stage. State police said about ten 
fire engines entered the grounds and firemen were working to put 
out the fire as thousands of fans watched. No information was 
available on whether there were any injuries as a result of the 
fires. State police said that by late afternoon more than 70,000 
people had departed with few delays. 

</P>
<P>
	Dodgers 2, Diamondbacks 1  
</P>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Kevin Brown won a pitching duel with Randy  
Johnson and Eric Karros hit his 200th career home run last night as 
the Los Angeles Dodgers snapped a five-game losing streak by 
beating the Arizona Diamondbacks 2-1. Brown allowed just three hits 
and an unearned run over eight innings to end Arizona's five-game 
winning streak and prevent the Diamondbacks from sweeping three 
from the Dodgers. 

</P>
<P>
	Rangers 4, Devil Rays 3  
</P>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- John Wetteland may have gotten his  
velocity back, but the Tampa Bay Devil Rays still gave him a scare. 
Wetteland got his major league-leading 29th save by striking out 
Aaron Ledesma and Rich Butler with the tying run on third in the 
ninth inning of the Rangers' 4-3 win over the Devil Rays on Sunday. 
The Rangers have won eight straight and are 10-1 since the All-Star 
break. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS  
  	   	
