<DOCNO> APW19990725.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-25 17:00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Passengers Fly Europe Cheap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BISHOP'S STORTFORD, Britain (AP) -- David Leport flaunted his  
boarding pass like a card shark with a winning hand. 
</P>
<P>
	The engineering student paid all of $27 for a round-trip ticket  
home to Dinard, France, on the regional airline Ryanair. 
</P>
<P>
	``It costs me more to park my car here for five days than it  
does to take this flight,'' Leport, 25, said recently at Stansted 
Airport north of London. 
</P>
<P>
	Like Leport, a growing number of Europeans are traveling to and  
from small, often remote airports in order to save big money on 
international flights. 
</P>
<P>
	Low-cost airlines spawned by the recent deregulation of Europe's  
aviation industry are able to offer cheaper fares by avoiding many 
of the costlier, big-city airports favored by their larger rivals. 
</P>
<P>
	While British Airways flies from Heathrow and Gatwick, London's  
two main airports, newcomer easyJet operates from a much smaller 
airport in the outlying town of Luton, 32 miles north of London. 
</P>
<P>
	Air France serves Charles de Gaulle and Orly airports in Paris,  
but low-cost carrier Debonair flies to Cergy Pontoise, a 
little-used airport in an industrial zone of the French capital. 
</P>
<P>
	These second-tier airports can be an hour's drive from the  
nearest big city. Yet the surge in flights suggests that 
bargain-hunters are only too happy to fly to them, even if it means 
connecting to their final destinations by bus or train. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are no queues for taxis and no queues for check-in.  
There's just not the same stress level as at the bigger, more 
congested airports,'' said Ethel Power, a spokeswoman for 
Dublin-based Ryanair. 
</P>
<P>
	Inspired by Southwest Airlines and other low-cost U.S. carriers,  
the regional upstarts are attracting customers despite their 
no-frills service and spotty record for punctuality. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the new airlines are based in Britain, where aviation  
authorities have been among the strongest supporters of the 
deregulation that began in Europe in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're not trying to steal market share from established  
airlines. What they're trying to do is stimulate additional demand 
that wouldn't have been there otherwise, through the introduction 
of low fares,'' said Guy Kekwick, an analyst in London with the 
U.S. investment bank Goldman Sachs. 
</P>
<P>
	Low-cost airlines making short, regional flights command less  
than 5 percent of Europe's aviation market, but they're growing 
fast. 
</P>
<P>
	Passenger traffic at Luton Airport, home to easyJet and  
Debonair, has increased by almost a third in each of the past two 
years. EasyJet had two flights a day when it began operating from 
Luton in 1995; today, it has 40. 
</P>
<P>
	Stansted, 35 miles north of London in Bishop's Stortford, has  
seen similar rates of growth. 
</P>
<P>
	Some big carriers such as Lufthansa and Alitalia, are responding  
with plans for similar low-cost subsidiaries of their own. British 
Airways' entry into the market is called Go. 
</P>
<P>
	The big winners from this trend are customers.  
</P>
<P>
	Debonair, for example, flies from Luton to Rome for a round-trip  
fare of $188. By comparison, a typical economy-class ticket on a 
Lufthansa flight from Heathrow Airport to Rome costs $306. 
</P>
<P>
	Direct comparisons with fares on U.S. domestic flights are hard  
to make, due to the myriad special fares possible for flights on 
both sides of the Atlantic. But air travel has typically cost less 
in the United States than in Europe, largely because deregulation 
of the American airline industry began some 20 years earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	To help keeps fares to a minimum, the low-cost carriers have  
stripped their in-flight service to its bare essentials, making 
passengers pay for drinks and forgoing in-flight meals. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody ever gives you champagne on the bus. Why are consumers  
brought up to expect that on a plane?'' said easyJet spokesman 
James Rothnie. 
</P>
<P>
	Strict regulations in Europe discourage low-cost airlines from  
cutting corners on safety. The downside to flying with them is 
suggested by anecdotal evidence of delays and penalties for 
changing departure dates. 
</P>
<P>
	But independents like easyJet and Debonair say their fortunes  
hinge on whether they can compete with the low-cost subsidiaries of 
the big airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	And because they fly along some of the same routes, competition  
between the smaller airlines is all the more intense. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's shared madness,'' said Franco Mancassola, Debonair's  
founder and chief executive. ``This business could thrive for all 
of us, even the little guys, if we allow it to develop with 
intelligence instead of trying to muscle each other away from 
routes.'' 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
