<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-25 20:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Plane Wreckage Found in Colombia  
</P>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Wreckage spotted today on a mountainside  
in southwestern Colombia might be that of a U.S. Army plane that 
disappeared while on a counternarcotics mission over 
rebel-dominated territory, the U.S. Army said. U.S. officials say 
the plane was on a routine mission over an area where drug crops 
are grown when it disappeared from radar screens. Its 
disappearance, however, was likely to heighten speculation in 
Colombia that Washington is getting deeply involved in the 
country's 35-year civil war. 

</P>
<P>
	Handyman Arrested in Yosemite Murder  
</P>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- A hotel maintenance man arrested in  
the beheading of a naturalist at Yosemite National Park is expected 
to be arraigned tomorrow, the FBI said. Cary Stayner, 37, was 
accused of killing Joie Ruth Armstrong, 26, whose decapitated body 
was found near her Yosemite housing on Thursday. Stayner, who is 
also a suspect in the killings of three park sightseers earlier 
this year, was arrested yesterday. 

</P>
<P>
	Venezuelan Leftist Coalition Wins  
</P>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- President Hugo Chavez's leftist  
coalition won an overwhelming majority of a constitutional assembly 
in nationwide elections today, giving the former coup leader vast 
new power to carry out his ``social revolution.'' With 78 percent 
of the vote counted, Chavez's Patriotic Pole coalition had 119 of 
the assembly's 128 seats up for grabs today, according to official 
results from the National Electoral Council. 

</P>
<P>
	Cuba Detains 4 Suspected Smugglers  
</P>
<P>
	HAVANA (AP) -- Cuban authorities have detained four men from  
Florida after their two speedboats were intercepted in the latest 
arrests of suspected smugglers, official news media reported today. 
The men were arrested off the Cuban coast about an hour apart 
Wednesday at two locations in the western province of Pinar del 
Rio, the Communist daily Granma and other local media reported. The 
arrests bring to 30 the number of U.S. residents held by the Cuban 
government on charges of smuggling emigrants from Cuba's shores. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO, UN Try To Rebuild Confidence  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO and the United Nations tried  
today to bolster confidence in their Kosovo mission, shaken by the 
massacre of 14 Serbian farmers in what officials called a 
deliberate attempt to wreck peacekeeping efforts. Belgrade demanded 
an urgent meeting of the U.N. Security Council on ways to stop 
ethnic violence in Kosovo and insisted Yugoslav forces be allowed 
back into the Serbian province, the state-run Tanjug news agency 
reported yesterday. 

</P>
<P>
	Western Wildfires Being Contained  
</P>
<P>
	RENO, Nev. (AP) -- Firefighters kept watch for rattlesnakes today  
as they battled a pair of fires that had burned more than 30,000 
acres near Reno and a Navy bombing range to the east. About 500 
firefighters had completely surrounded a 15,500-acre wildfire in 
the steep canyons about 8 miles east of Reno, and the columns of 
smoke that were visible from the city had started to dissipate. 
Elsewhere in the West, a week-old fire in California's Santa 
Barbara County had burned 14,200 acres. 

</P>
<P>
	TV Commentator Agronsky Dies  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Longtime television commentator Martin  
Agronsky has died of heart failure in Washington at age 84. 
Agronsky is considered one of the pioneers of the ``talking heads'' 
television news format that features journalists talking to each 
other in a group about the latest events, rather than interviewing 
newsmakers. Agronsky began in newspaper journalism, then became a 
war correspondent on radio. From 1943 until he retired in 1988 he 
was a Washington correspondent, foreign correspondent and 
commentator for U.S. television. 

</P>
<P>
	Yankees Defeat Indians 2-1  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- After striking out in his first three at-bats,  
Ricky Ledee homered in the ninth inning tonight to give the New 
York Yankees a 2-1 win over Cleveland and a three-game sweep of the 
Indians. Ledee, a left-handed batter, appeared to be on the way to 
strikeout No. 4 with an 0-2 count and left-hander Ricardo Rincon 
(0-2) on the mound. But he easily cleared the right-field fence 
with his fourth homer of the season. 

</P>
<P>
	Cardinals Defeat Rockies 6-4  
</P>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Mark McGwire hit his 35th home run, pulling him  
within one of major league leader Sammy Sosa, and the St. Louis 
Cardinals beat the Colorado Rockies 6-4 tonight for a three-game 
sweep. McGwire homered in the seventh inning, his eighth in 11 
games, then left with tightness in his back. McGwire has 12 homers 
in July but just two in 13 at-bats at Coors Field. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ELIZABETH A. KENNEDY  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
