<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Wreckage Found in Colombia  
</P>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Wreckage spotted today on a mountainside  
in southwestern Colombia might be that of a U.S. army plane that 
disappeared while on a counternarcotics mission over 
rebel-dominated territory, the U.S. Army said. U.S. officials say 
the plane was on a routine mission over an area where drug crops 
are grown when it disappeared from radar screens. Its 
disappearance, however, was likely to heighten speculation in 
Colombia that Washington is getting deeply involved in the 
country's 35-year civil war. 

</P>
<P>
	Handyman Arrested in Yosemite Murder  
</P>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- A hotel maintenance man who was  
arrested yesterday in the beheading of a naturalist at Yosemite 
National Park is expected to be arraigned tomorrow, the FBI said. 
Cary Stayner, 37, was accused of killing Joie Ruth Armstrong, 26, 
whose decapitated body was found near her Yosemite housing on 
Thursday. Stayner is also a suspect in the killings of three park 
sightseers earlier this year. 

</P>
<P>
	Venezuelan Leftist Coalition Wins  
</P>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- President Hugo Chavez's leftist  
coalition won an overwhelming majority of a constitutional assembly 
in nationwide elections today, giving the former coup leader vast 
new power to carry out his ``social revolution.'' With 78 percent 
of the vote counted, Chavez's Patriotic Pole coalition had 119 of 
the assembly's 128 seats up for grabs today, according to official 
results from the National Electoral Council. 

</P>
<P>
	Shuttle May Have Leaked Fuel  
</P>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Space shuttle Columbia may have been  
leaking hydrogen fuel all the way to orbit last week from one of 
its main engines, NASA said today. If it proves to be a leak as 
photographs suggest, the engine could have shut down abruptly if 
more fuel had seeped out, resulting in a never-before-attempted 
emergency landing within minutes of launch. As it turned out, 
Columbia made it safely to orbit Friday under the control of Air 
Force Col. Eileen Collins, the first woman to command a U.S. 
spaceship. 

</P>
<P>
	Western Wildfires Being Contained  
</P>
<P>
	RENO, Nev. (AP) -- Firefighters kept watch for rattlesnakes today  
as they battled a pair of fires that had burned more than 30,000 
acres near Reno and a Navy bombing range to the east. About 500 
firefighters had completely surrounded a 15,500-acre wildfire in 
the steep canyons about 8 miles east of Reno, and the columns of 
smoke that were visible from the city had started to dissipate. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Urges Calm in China, Taiwan  
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Washington's top liaison with Taiwan today  
urged Beijing and Taipei to cool tensions and avoid war, but said 
the United States would not mediate between them. Richard Bush said 
Washington wanted the two sides to engage in more dialogue and 
avoid provocations, an apparent criticism of a recent statement by 
Taiwan President Lee Teng-hui that demanded Taiwan and China be 
recognized as equally legitimate states. 

</P>
<P>
	Passengers Fly Europe Cheap  
</P>
<P>
	BISHOP'S STORTFORD, Britain (AP) -- Low-cost airlines spawned by  
the recent deregulation of Europe's aviation industry are able to 
offer cheaper fares by avoiding many of the costlier, big-city 
airports favored by their larger rivals. These second-tier airports 
can be an hour's drive from the nearest big city. Yet the surge in 
flights suggests that bargain-hunters are only too happy to fly to 
them. 

</P>
<P>
	Internet Security Fights Back  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Internet security researchers at Georgia Tech  
believe the neural networks they are working on may be the key to 
stopping hackers. Even though Georgia Tech's The Sentinel Project 
doesn't ``think,'' the group of programs is set up in different 
``nodes'' much like a human brain. The network is designed to 
recognize abnormal data, which could signal that someone has broken 
into the system. 

</P>
