<HEADLINE> Bengals' Pickens May Not Be At Camp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- The leading receiver in Cincinnati Bengals  
history is threatening to quit rather than play one more day in 
stripes. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bengals opening training camp this week assuming Carl  
Pickens will stay true to his word. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have to go into it thinking that he's not going to be  
here,'' coach Bruce Coslet said. ``I'd love to have him back. I've 
said that all along, but what else can you say? That's why we made 
him the franchise player -- that's how much we think of him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pickens made it clear that he wanted to leave as an unrestricted  
free agent. Instead, the Bengals designated him their franchise 
player, meaning he has to stay for $3.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Pickens has threatened to retire. So far, he's given no  
indication he'll be in Georgetown, Ky., when training camp opens 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he wants to stay home and forego $3.5 million, that would  
be a decision that he can make, but I'd scratch my head a little 
bit about it,'' general manager Mike Brown said. ``Sometimes these 
things spiral down and crash. I would like to think at some point 
he would come around.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pickens, 29, became the franchise's career leader in receptions  
and receiving touchdowns last season. He has been the Bengals' 
leading receiver for four of the past five seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bengals are willing to trade Pickens, just as they did Dan  
Wilkinson after they made him their franchise player. But no one 
has offered a deal to their liking. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not going to have a fire sale,'' Brown said.  
</P>
<P>
	That leaves Coslet to plan for an offense that will function  
without Pickens. Darnay Scott would become the No. 1 receiver. No 
other receiver had as many as 20 catches for the Bengals last 
season. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
