<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No Frenchman Has Won Tour Since '85 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARPAJON, France (AP) -- Christian Mahe, a 17-year-old cycling  
fan, is one of the millions of French teen-agers who never saw a 
countryman win the Tour de France, the quintessential French event. 
</P>
<P>
	Proudly wearing a polka dot cap in honor of French rider Richard  
Virenque, he was among the crowds at the start line of Sunday's 
final stage, from Arpajon to Paris. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a real shame that one of our guys can't win. After all,  
this is the Tour de France,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mais oui.  
</P>
<P>
	Not since 1985 has a Frenchman pedaled into Paris wearing the  
famous yellow jersey of the champion. This year's race, which ended 
in American Lance Armstrong's remarkable triumph, marked the first 
time since 1926 that a Frenchman didn't win a single stage of the 
Tour. And it was only the fourth time since World War II that one 
didn't figure in the top five overall. 
</P>
<P>
	Though nothing seemed to diminish their enthusiasm for the  
world's top cycling event, French fans are nonetheless bewildered 
at the performance of their riders. 
</P>
<P>
	They're bewildered about other sports, too.  
</P>
<P>
	The Champs-Elysees, where the Tour's finale took place, is where  
hundreds of thousands streamed a year ago to bask in the glow of 
France's surprising World Cup triumph. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, however, there hasn't been much to celebrate.  
</P>
<P>
	Last Sunday, Jean Van de Velde went from sure winner to eventual  
playoff loser in seven shocking strokes at the British Open, the 
most stunning collapse in major championship golf history. 
</P>
<P>
	The national rugby team is coming off a terrible string of  
losses, including 54-7 to New Zealand. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the Tour's inception in 1903, French riders have won a  
record 36 times. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1970s and 1980s, the legendary French duo of Bernard  
Hinault and Laurent Fignon dominated the race, winning seven times. 
</P>
<P>
	But the last triumph for a French rider was Hinault's way back  
in 1985. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a shame for the public that a French rider didn't win a  
stage. It isn't so good for French morale,'' Tour director 
Jean-Marie Leblanc said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe the quality of French cycling isn't up to scratch at the  
moment. But don't forget Jalabert isn't here,'' he said, meaning 
the world's No. 1 rider, Laurent Jalabert. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Italy's Marco Pantani won. In 1997 it was Germany's  
Jan Ullrich and the year before it was Denmark's Bjarne Riis. 
</P>
<P>
	In each of the last four years, the French have had only one  
top-five rider. On Sunday, Virenque was their best-placed finisher 
-- eighth. 
</P>
<P>
	French cyclist Thierry Gouvenou noted that this year's race  
began with 43 Italians, compared with only 39 Frenchmen. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Tour is getting more international, so it is logical that  
we aren't winning,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the French media was making no excuses.  
</P>
<P>
	The headline in the sports daily L'Equipe: ``The French, what a  
mess!'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
