<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Banned Fish Becomes Hot Item in Mo. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	REPUBLIC, Mo. (AP) -- A tiny fish that became a cause celebre in  
this city within a landlocked state has continued reeling in 
national interest. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal court ruled this month that the Christian fish symbol  
-- known as an ichthus -- had to be removed from the city's seal 
because it violated the constitutional separation of church and 
state. 
</P>
<P>
	But ever since the ichthus-bearing seal started coming down last  
week, the little fish seems to be more popular than ever. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had a lot of people call from all over the country  
asking what we're going to do with this stuff,'' said City 
Administrator Dean P. Thompson as he stood in his office, cluttered 
with fish-adorned lapel pins, buttons, patches, business cards, 
stationery, a clock and other memorabilia. 
</P>
<P>
	The seal also adorned city trucks, signs, flags and letterheads.  
</P>
<P>
	``I had a guy call in who said, `I'll give you $100 for the city  
limit sign,''' Thompson continued with a smile. ``A guy from 
Georgia said he collects business cards. He said, `Send me a 
card.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson said an Internet auction was a likely possibility, with  
proceeds going toward the estimated $20,000 needed to remove the 
seal from city property. 
</P>
<P>
	Most folks here couldn't help giggling a bit at the 15 minutes  
of fame the fish symbol brought this quiet little suburb located 
just west of Springfield. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fish died. You suppose they're going to have a fish fry?''  
quipped Milton King, commander at the local Veterans of Foreign 
Wars hall. 
</P>
<P>
	The fish -- a symbol of Christianity since the time of ancient  
Rome -- won out in a 1990 design contest to create a new city seal 
and flag for Republic, population 8,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The seal's designer, Marilyn Schexsnayder, said the intention of  
the simple design was for the fish to represent all religions, not 
just Christianity. 
</P>
<P>
	But Jean Webb, a practitioner of Wicca, or witchcraft, said when  
she moved to Republic in 1995 the symbol made her feel unwelcome. 
Last year, the Ozarks chapter of the American Civil Liberties Union 
sued on her behalf, seeking to have the ichthus removed. 
</P>
<P>
	The Board of Aldermen refused, and called on local residents to  
raise as much as $100,000 to defend the fish. 
</P>
<P>
	When a federal court ruled in the ACLU's favor July 9, the city  
backed down. Aldermen voted last week to can the fish, with Mayor 
Doug Boatright casting the tiebreaker in a 5-4 vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's nice to see that even in southwest Missouri, where the  
church you go to really does matter ... it's nice to see that the 
Constitution can still win out,'' said Ms. Webb, who has since 
moved from Republic. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd say the mayor made the right move,'' barber John Parker  
said as he trimmed a customer's hair. ``It's time to get over this 
and get on to something else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Most of us here don't think much of the ACLU,'' Parker added  
as a shop full of customers nodded their agreement. ``But the city 
didn't have enough money to fight this, and they were going to have 
to dip into taxpayers' funds.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it would have been fine to leave it on there,'' he  
said. ``But if it was going to take a lot of tax money to do it, 
then it just wasn't worth it'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some even agreed with Ms. Webb.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm for the separation of church and state,'' said Dallas  
Combs. ``I don't think the government should get involved in 
anybody's religion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In any case, King said, last week's court decision won't alter  
much but the signs at City Hall. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not going to change this town any because that little  
logo is not on there,'' he said. ``It's still a nice little town.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990725.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-25 23:20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Smokers Rolling Own Cigarettes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, Ga. (AP) -- When cigarette prices jumped last fall, Tom  
Hagen figured he had two choices: quit or roll his own. 
</P>
<P>
	He's still puffing. Like thousands of others, he now gets his  
cigarettes the old-fashioned way. 
</P>
<P>
	Rolling your own -- formerly the exclusive territory of farmers  
and truck drivers -- has suddenly become urban chic, says Adam 
Marsh, president of M&AMP;R Holdings in New York City, which produces 
``Farmers' Gold'' tobacco. 
</P>
<P>
	``I see Yuppie types. I saw a young woman in a cafe in the East  
Village who took out a little pouch of tobacco, took out some 
papers and rolled her own,'' Marsh says. 
</P>
<P>
	Marsh's company plans to introduce a make-your-own kit later  
this summer with a cigarette machine, tobacco and all the other 
accessories. 
</P>
<P>
	Joyce White, owner of Royal Cigar Co. in Atlanta, says sales of  
make-your-own supplies ``are off the wall.'' Royal Cigar has an 
Internet business that offers 11 rolling machine models ranging 
from $4 to $20 and more than 30 brands of tobacco. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's anyone from age 30 up to the 90s,'' says Mrs. White. ``I  
had a woman in her 80s call me and say she's rolling. It crosses 
every line I can think of.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Peter Stokkebye, whose California-based firm sells several  
European blends through tobacconists, says the practice was all but 
extinct until the multibillion-dollar tobacco settlement drove up 
prices. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe that within a year or so it'll probably grow to 5  
percent of consumption, and ... that's a lot of tobacco,'' 
Stokkebye says. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp. controls 62 percent of the  
cigarette-making kits and loose tobacco that make up the 
roll-your-own market. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales of loose tobacco are up 30 percent over last year,  
spokesman Mark Smith says. The company expects sales of the tobacco 
and make-your-own accessories to reach $110 million this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Cigarette prices went up 45 cents a pack last year after four  
tobacco makers agreed to pay $206 billion to states for the cost of 
caring for sick smokers. They had previously settled with four 
states for about $40 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the federal excise tax on cigarettes, now at 24  
cents per pack, will jump 10 cents on Jan. 1 and 5 cents more in 
2002. Some states also levy high taxes on cigarettes, including 
California's 87 cents per pack and Alaska's and Hawaii's $1 per 
pack. 
</P>
<P>
	In contrast, prices for loose tobacco have remained fairly  
stable because the federal government and many states don't tax it. 
In an effort to partially close that loophole, loose tobacco will 
be subject to a 4 cents-per-pound federal excise tax starting in 
January. 
</P>
<P>
	In Albany, where a carton of Marlboro costs about $25, a smoker  
would pay about $11 using Brown &AMP; Williamson's kit -- $7.50 for the 
tobacco, $3.00 for tubes and filters and $3.50 for a machine that 
can be reused. 
</P>
<P>
	Hagen said his make-your-own cigarettes cost $8 to $9 per  
carton. He gets his supplies from a mail-order business and from 
Joe's Smokehouse, a local tobacco shop. Owner Joe Carter sells more 
than a dozen brands of rolling tobacco, some imported, and several 
cigarette-making machines. He also stocks rolling paper and 
cigarette tubes with filters. 
</P>
<P>
	There are two basic types of machines. One rolls the cigarettes  
on a fabric band. Gummed paper holds the cigarette together. The 
other stuffs the tobacco into the paper tubes that already have the 
filters inserted at one end. 
</P>
<P>
	Carter says he's stocked roll-your-own supplies since his store  
opened in 1996, but has seen higher demand since the tobacco 
settlement. He says his customers come from all walks of life. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think most of them feel the government is trying to force  
them out of smoking and they don't want to be forced,'' Carter 
says. 
</P>
<P>
	Adds Hagen, ``I only wish I had started handrolling long ago  
because I have learned to like it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
