<DOCNO> APW19990725.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-25 19:40:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Robin Yount Thanks Friends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. (AP) -- On Robin Yount's big day, he took time  
to remember three workers killed while building a new ballpark in 
the city where he found baseball greatness. 
</P>
<P>
	``As great a day as this is for us up here, we have to remember  
there are people out there who are hurting,'' Yount said Sunday 
during his acceptance speech for his induction into baseball's Hall 
of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're often reminded as to how quickly things can be taken  
from us. My heart goes out to the families of the men who lost 
their lives in the construction of the new stadium in Milwaukee.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On July 14, a 567-foot crane at Miller Park, what will be the  
Milwaukee Brewers' new stadium, collapsed, killing three workers 
helping to lift a 400-ton section of roof into place. 
</P>
<P>
	``The game of life can sometimes be too short,'' Yount said,  
concluding his speech. ``So play it with everything you've got.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yount, the first player to wear a Brewers' cap into the Hall of  
Fame, ranks 15th on the career hits list with 3,142. 
</P>
<P>
	He spent all 20 years with Milwaukee, spurning chances to play  
with better teams, and is one of only three players to win the MVP 
award at two positions (shortstop, 1982; center field, 1989). Yount 
retired in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guess, simply Robin, all I can say is on behalf of myself  
and the fans of Milwaukee and Wisconsin it has been an unbelievable 
privilege,'' said former Brewers owner Bud Selig, now commissioner 
of baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	Yount a huge crowd that included hooting and clapping Brewers  
fans that, as a boy, he spent hours playing baseball with family 
and friends and dreamed of playing professional ball. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was lucky. That dream came true,'' Yount said.  
</P>
<P>
	His dreams of hitting a homer in a World Series and playing in  
an All-Star game also came true -- but he also dreamed of making the 
final catch in a World Series and being mobbed by his teammates. 
</P>
<P>
	``Well, I guess all my dreams didn't come true,'' Yount said,  
bringing chuckles from the audience. The 1982 Brewers lost to the 
St. Louis Cardinals in seven games. 
</P>
<P>
	``But what I'd really like to tell you is, I never dreamed of  
being in the Hall of Fame. Standing here with all these great 
players was beyond any of my dreams,'' Yount added. ``I couldn't 
have handpicked a better class to go to Cooperstown with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yount was inducted Sunday along with Orlando Cepeda, Nolan Ryan,  
George Brett, late umpire Nestor Chylak, Negro leagues pitcher 
Smokey Joe Williams and turn-of-the-century manager Frank Selee. 
</P>
<P>
	Yount also heaped praise on former coaches dating back to his  
little league and high school days. He thanked people from a list 
that was a who's who of Brewers history. 
</P>
<P>
	There was former owner Selig, ``who truly cared about his  
players,'' and former managers, such as Del Crandall, Harvey Kuehn, 
George Bamberger and current manager Phil Garner. 
</P>
<P>
	Then there were the players, such as Henry Aaron, Paul Molitor,  
Cecil Cooper, Gorman Thomas, Larry Hisle, Rollie Fingers and Jim 
Gantner. The list went on and on. 
</P>
<P>
	``To have guys like this not only as teammates but as friends  
made it where I couldn't wait to go to the ballpark every day,'' 
Yount said. 
</P>
<P>
	Yount even mentioned the Brewers' radio announcer Bob Uecker --  
``not a teammate, but definitely one of the guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Molitor, likely to be the next Brewer inducted into the Hall of  
Fame, was on hand for the ceremony. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm glad that he's enjoying it and savoring it and having a  
chance to share with a lot of friends and family,'' Molitor said. 
``I know personally I can never measure how much he meant to my 
career, his friendship and the things that he taught me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tim Vanderhoef, a fan from Kenosha, Wis., spoke of his trip to  
Cooperstown as of a pilgrimage. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a religious thing. We go to the homeland, or wherever  
Robin Yount is to be honored,'' said Vanderhoef, who was wearing a 
Brewers cap, and sported long red hair and a moustache that made 
him a Yount look-a-like. 
</P>
<P>
	Selig said he was impressed by the fans' dedication.  
</P>
<P>
	``You see all these people with Brewer caps and Brewer jerseys  
and Yount jerseys,'' Selig said. ``There's so many people here from 
Milwaukee and Wisconsin. This is big. This is really big.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``OK, now's the time when I'm supposed to wake up from all of  
this,'' Yount said during his speech. ``I mean it's OK, it's been a 
great dream. But if in fact this is reality, then with all due 
respect, Mr. Gehrig, today I consider myself the luckiest man on 
the face of the earth.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
